{"title_page": "Edward Marjoribanks, 2nd Baron Tweedmouth", "text_new": "{{other people|Edward Marjoribanks}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Lord Tweedmouth\n| honorific-suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|KT|PC}}\n| image = Portrait of Edward Marjoribanks, 2nd Baron Tweedmouth.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption =\n\n| order1 = [[Lord President of the Council]]\n| term_start1 = 12 April 1908\n| term_end1 = 13 October 1908\n| monarch1 = [[Edward VII of the United Kingdom|Edward VII]]\n| primeminister1 = [[H. H. Asquith]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Robert Crewe-Milnes, 1st Marquess of Crewe|The Earl of Crewe]]\n| successor1 = [[Henry Fowler, 1st Viscount Wolverhampton|The Viscount Wolverhampton]]\n\n| order2 = [[List of the First Lords of the Admiralty|First Lord of the Admiralty]]\n| term_start2 = 10 December 1905\n| term_end2 = 12 April 1908\n| monarch2 = [[Edward VII of the United Kingdom|Edward VII]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Henry Campbell-Bannerman|Sir Henry Campbell-Bannerman]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Frederick Campbell, 3rd Earl Cawdor|The Earl Cawdor]]\n| successor2 = [[Reginald McKenna]]\n\n| order3 = [[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster]]\n| term_start3 = 28 May 1894\n| term_end3 = 21 June 1895\n| monarch3 = [[Victoria of the United Kingdom|Victoria]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery|The Earl of Rosebery]]\n| predecessor3 = [[James Bryce, 1st Viscount Bryce|James Bryce]]\n| successor3 = [[Henry James, 1st Baron James of Hereford|The Lord James of Hereford]]\n\n| order4 = [[Lord Privy Seal]]\n| term_start4 = 10 March 1894\n| term_end4 = 21 June 1895\n| monarch4 = [[Victoria of the United Kingdom|Victoria]]\n| primeminister4 = [[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery|The Earl of Rosebery]]\n| predecessor4 = [[William Ewart Gladstone]]\n| successor4 = [[R. A. Cross, 1st Viscount Cross|The Viscount Cross]]\n\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1849|7|8}}\n| birth_place =\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1909|9|15|1849|7|8}}\n| death_place =\n| nationality = British\n| party = [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]]\n| alma_mater =\n| spouse = {{marriage|Lady Fanny Spencer-Churchill (1853\u20131904)<br>|1873|1904|end=her death}}\n}}\n\n'''Edward Marjoribanks, 2nd Baron Tweedmouth''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|KT|PC}} (8 July 1849 \u2013 15 September 1909), was a moderate<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zrdjEV9zY5MC&pg=PA80&dq=tweedmouth%20moderate&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CD8Q6AEwBWoVChMIrfe5nfO8xwIViVjbCh1jDgEs#v=onepage&q=tweedmouth%20moderate&f=false|title=Defending the Empire: The Conservative Party and British Defence Policy, 1899-1915|first=Rhodri|last=Williams|date=1 January 1991|publisher=Yale University Press|accessdate=29 January 2017|via=Google Books}}</ref> British [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] statesman who sat in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] from 1880 until 1894 when he inherited his peerage and then sat in the [[House of Lords]]. He served in various capacities in the Liberal governments of the late 19th and early 20th centuries.\n\n==Biography==\nTweedmouth was the son of [[Dudley Marjoribanks, 1st Baron Tweedmouth]], and Isabella, daughter of [[Sir James Hogg, 1st Baronet]].<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p10633.htm|title=Person Page|publisher=|accessdate=29 January 2017}}</ref> [[Ishbel Hamilton-Gordon, Marchioness of Aberdeen and Temair]], was his sister. He is descended from Joseph Marjoribanks, a wine and fish merchant in Edinburgh who died in 1635 and is thought to have been the grandson of Thomas Marjoribanks of Ratho,<ref name = MBJournal3b>Marjoribanks, Roger. \"Marjoribanks of Lees\", [http://marjorib.awardspace.co.uk/JIssue3.html The Marjoribanks Journal Number 3], page 14, June 1995. Accessed on 22 May 2010</ref> head of the lowland [[Clan Marjoribanks]].<ref>[http://www.marjoribanks.net Clan Marjoribanks web site] accessed 29 April 2010.</ref> He was educated at [[Christ Church, Oxford]], but expelled in 1870 following a prank involving that led to the damage of college sculptures.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Curthoys |first1=Judith |title=Practical joke, or wanton vandalism? The Library Statues Row - May 1870 |url=https://www.chch.ox.ac.uk/blog/practical-joke-or-wanton-vandalism-library-statues-row-may-1870 |website=www.chch.ox.ac.uk |publisher=Christ Church, Oxford University |accessdate=2 May 2019}}</ref> \n\n===Political career===\n[[File:Edward Marjoribanks, 2nd Baron Tweedmouth.jpg|thumb|right|Tweedmouth]]\nTweedmouth was returned to Parliament for [[Berwickshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Berwickshire]] in 1880, a seat he held until 1894.<ref name=\"leighrayment\">{{cite web|url=http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Bcommons2.htm|publisher=leighrayment.com|title=House of Commons: Bedford to Berwick upon Tweed|accessdate=3 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224095640/http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Bcommons2.htm|archive-date=24 February 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> The seat had been held earlier in the century by his [[great-uncle]], [[Sir John Marjoribanks, 1st Baronet]] and cousin, [[Charles Albany Marjoribanks]].\n\nHe served under [[William Ewart Gladstone]] as [[Comptroller of the Household]] in between February and July 1886<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=25558 |date=12 February 1886 |page=682 }}</ref> and was sworn of the [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|Privy Council]] the same year.<ref name=\"leighrayment2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.leighrayment.com/pcouncil/pcouncil2.htm|publisher=leighrayment.com|title= Privy Counsellors: 1836\u20131914 |accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref> When the Liberals returned to power under Gladstone in 1892, he was made [[Parliamentary Secretary to the Treasury]] (chief whip).<ref name=\"leighrayment.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.leighrayment.com/peers/peersT2.htm|publisher=leighrayment.com|title= Peerage: Tiberris to Tyrrell |accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref> He succeeded his father in the barony in March 1894, only a few days before Gladstone resigned and [[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery|Lord Rosebery]] became Prime Minister. Rosebery appointed Tweedmouth [[Lord Privy Seal]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=26496 |date=20 March 1894 |page=1661 }}</ref> with a seat in the cabinet, and in May 1894 he also became [[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster]]. He retained these posts until the government fell in 1895.<ref name=\"leighrayment.com\"/>\n\nAfter ten years in opposition, the Liberals again came to power in December 1905 under [[Henry Campbell-Bannerman|Sir Henry Campbell-Bannerman]], who appointed Tweedmouth [[List of the First Lords of the Admiralty|First Lord of the Admiralty]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=27866 |date=22 December 1905 |page=9172 }}</ref> with a seat in the cabinet. In early 1908 he was criticised for corresponding with German emperor [[William II of Germany|William II]] on the British naval programme. The matter was referred to the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]]. [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] [[H. H. Asquith]] eventually stated that the correspondence was \"a purely personal and private communication, conceived in an entirely friendly spirit\" and no action was taken.<ref name=obit/>  However, when Asquith succeeded Campbell-Bannerman as Prime Minister in April 1908 Tweedmouth was removed as head of the Admiralty and became [[Lord President of the Council]].<ref name=\"leighrayment.com\"/> He suffered a nervous breakdown in June 1908, a condition which was said to partly explain his indiscretion in communicating with the German Emperor on naval matters. Although his health later recovered, he resigned in October 1908.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1908/09/29/archives/lord-tweedmouth-resigns-quits-presidency-of-the-council-but-his.html|title=LORD TWEEDMOUTH RESIGNS.; Quits Presidency of the Council, but His Mental Condition Is Improved.|date=29 September 1908|publisher=|accessdate=29 January 2017|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> He was made a [[Order of the Thistle|Knight of the Thistle]] in 1908.<ref name=\"leighrayment3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.leighrayment.com/orders/thistle.htm|publisher=leighrayment.com|title=Knights of the Thistle |accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nAn advocate of worker's rights<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ucd_AAAAQBAJ&pg=PT72&dq=Lord%20Tweedmouth%20eighty%20club%20speech%20working%20class&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCYQ6AEwAWoVChMI3MHHiJ3jxwIV65zbCh3zxgyO#v=onepage&q=Lord%20Tweedmouth%20eighty%20club%20speech%20working%20class&f=false|title=Edward Carpenter and Late Victorian Radicalism|first1=Tony|last1=Brown|first2=Thomas N.|last2=Corns|date=21 August 2013|publisher=Routledge|accessdate=29 January 2017|via=Google Books}}</ref> and social legislation,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/1905/may/09/workmens-compensation-bill-hl#S4V0145P0_19050509_HOL_105|title=WORKMEN'S COMPENSATION BILL [H.L.] (Hansard, 9 May 1905)|publisher=|accessdate=29 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/1901/mar/08/the-housing-problem-government-policy#S4V0090P0_19010308_HOL_53|title=THE HOUSING PROBLEM \u2014 GOVERNMENT POLICY. (Hansard, 8 March 1901)|publisher=|accessdate=29 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/1902/mar/13/factory-and-workshop-act-1901-amendment#S4V0104P0_19020313_HOL_31|title=FACTORY AND WORKSHOP ACT (1901) AMENDMENT BILL [H.L.] (Hansard, 13 March 1902)|publisher=|accessdate=29 January 2017}}</ref> Tweedmouth was supportive of the Liberal Party's alliance with the Labour Party in the lead-up to the 1906 General Election, believing that the Liberals could not win without it, and regarded as \u201chumbug\u201d the view that such an alliance meant class legislation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p9fTBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA167&dq=Lord%20Tweedmouth%20working%20class&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CDgQ6AEwBGoVChMIi_31np3jxwIVYoHbCh0HjAAf#v=onepage&q=Lord%20Tweedmouth%20working%20class&f=false|title=Liberal Hearts and Coronets: The Lives and Times of Ishbel Marjoribanks Gordon and John Campbell Gordon, the Aberdeens|first=Veronica|last=Strong-Boag|date=1 January 2015|publisher=University of Toronto Press|accessdate=29 January 2017|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nHe died on 15 September 1909.<ref name=obit>{{cite news |author= |title=Lord Tweedmouth Dead |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1909/09/16/archives/lord-tweedmouth-dead-his-correspondence-with-german-emperor-caused.html |quote= |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=16 September 1909 }}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nLord Tweedmouth married Lady Fanny Octavia Louise (1853\u20131904), daughter of [[John Spencer-Churchill, 7th Duke of Marlborough]] and aunt of [[Winston Churchill|Sir Winston Churchill]], in 1873. She reportedly died from cancer in August 1904, aged 51 \"at Lord Tweedmouth's Glen Affric shooting lodge\". They had a son and [[heir]]; [[Dudley Marjoribanks, 3rd Baron Tweedmouth|Dudley, 3rd Baron Tweedmouth]] (1874\u20131935).<ref>{{cite web|title=DEATH OF LADY TWEED MOUTH Lady Tweedmouth died last night at Lord Tweedmouth's shooting lodge, Glen Affric,  in Strathglass, Inverness-shire.|url=http://www.genesreunited.co.uk/searchbna/results?memberlastsubclass=none&searchhistorykey=0&keywords=lady%20tweedmouth%20glen%20affric%20lodge%20shooting&from=1875&to=1949|publisher=Edinburgh Evening News Midlothian, Scotland  |date= 6 August 1904|accessdate=13 January 2014|quote=DEATH OF LADY TWEED MOUTH Lady Tweed mouth died last night at Lord Tweedmouth's shooting lodge in Strathglass, Inverness-shire. Lady Fanny Occavia Louisa Spencer-Churchill was married to Lord Tweedmouth in 1873. She was the third daughter of the seventh Duke of.....}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=McCall|first1=Alison|title=Fanny Octavia Louisa Spencer-Churchill|url=http://womenofscotland.org.uk/women/fanny-octavia-louisa-spencer-churchill|date=6 April 2016|accessdate=29 January 2017|quote=She died of cancer in 1904}}</ref>\n\nLord Tweedmouth's parliamentary career saw him  reported as being the '''Laird of Guisachan and Glenaffric'''  who was, on occasions, \"in a fighting mood\".<ref>{{cite web|title=THE ABERDEEN JOURNAL, TUESDAY, NOVEMBER 22, 1898,|url=http://www.genesreunited.co.uk/searchbna/results?memberlastsubclass=none&searchhistorykey=0&keywords=laird%20tweedmouth%20glenaffric&from=1875&to=1949&page=4|publisher=Aberdeen Press and Journal Aberdeenshire, Scotland |date= 22 November 1898|accessdate=13 January 2015|quote= The laird of Guisachan and Glenaffric was in a fighting mood last night, and he devoted the main part of his address to an attack on Mr Chamberlain\u2019s Manchester speeches. Lord Tweedmouth does not affect the most...}}</ref>  Following Lady Tweedmouth's death, Lord Tweedmouth  sold the [[Laird]]ship of  [[Glen Affric]], the property including the Guisachan  Estate and deer park that his family had owned since the 1850s.<ref>{{cite web|title=ISHBEL LADY ABERDEEN AT INVERNESS|url=http://www.genesreunited.co.uk/searchbna/results?memberlastsubclass=none&searchhistorykey=0&keywords=lady%20of%20guisachan%20glen%20%20affric&from=1875&to=1949&page=1|publisher=The Scotsman Midlothian, Scotland |date= 14 December 1934|accessdate=29 January 2013|quote=....presided, spoke of Lady Aberdeen's connection with the Highlands and to the many happy days she spent in Glen Affric, which was then the property of her father. (i.e. Dudley Marjoribanks, 1st Baron Tweedmouth, died 1894)}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title=Golden Retriever | publisher=i5 Publishing | last=Pepper|first= Jeffrey G. | year=2012 | pages=27 | isbn=9781621870340}}</ref>  He was reported as being a \"generous [[laird]]\", who, like his father,  \"did much for the people\" of his estate; the \"ties which united the people of Glen Affric with the Laird and his lady were close\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000470/19080414/139/0006?_=1492211773772|work=The Berwickshire News|date=14 April 1908|page=6|title=The late Dowager Lady Tweedmouth|accessdate=15 April 2007|quote=Close were the ties which united the people of Glen Affric with the Laird and his lady. Secluded from the world...{{subscription required}}}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=ISHBEL, LADY ABERDEEN \u2014  The Home of Her Youth Revisited  - A HIGHLAND WELCOME|url=http://www.genesreunited.co.uk/searchbna/results?memberlastsubclass=none&searchhistorykey=0&keywords=laird%20and%20lady%20tweedmouth&from=1875&to=1949|publisher=The Scotsman Midlothian, Scotland |date= 15 December 1934|accessdate=13 January 2014|quote=Many present remembered Lady Aberdeen as the lovely daughter of Lord Tweedmouth, who, like his son who succeeded him, was a generous laird and did much for the estate.....and especially for the people of Guisachan}}</ref>\n\nLord Tweedmouth survived his wife by five years and died in September 1909, aged 60. He was succeeded in the barony by his son, [[Dudley Marjoribanks, 3rd Baron Tweedmouth|Dudley]].<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\"/>\n\n==The Rocking Chair Ranche==\nFrom 1883 until 1896, he was an owner of and investor in [[Rocking Chair Ranche]] located in [[Collingsworth County]], [[Texas]], along with his father, [[Dudley Marjoribanks, 1st Baron Tweedmouth|The 1st Baron Tweedmouth]], and his brother-in-law, [[John Hamilton-Gordon, 1st Marquess of Aberdeen and Temair|The 7th Earl of Aberdeen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/apr01|title=ROCKING CHAIR RANCH|first=Anderson H.|last=Allen|date=15 June 2010|publisher=|accessdate=29 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n;Secondary sources\n*{{cite book | editor-first=Charles | editor-last=Mosley | title=Burke's Peerage and Baronetage | place=London: The Boydell Press | date=2003 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Edward Marjoribanks, 2nd Baron Tweedmouth}}\n* {{Cite DNB|wstitle=Marjoribanks, Edward |short=x}}\n* {{hansard-contribs | mr-edward-marjoribanks | Edward Marjoribanks, 2nd Baron Tweedmouth }}\n* {{NPG name}}\n*[http://www.vandaprints.com/image.php?id=142557 Photograph of Lord Tweedmouth at vandaprints.com]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box | title=Member of Parliament for [[Berwickshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Berwickshire]] | before=[[Robert Baillie-Hamilton|Hon. Robert Baillie-Hamilton]] | after=[[Harold Tennant]] | years=1880\u20131894}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Comptroller of the Household]] | before=[[Lord Arthur Hill]] | after=[[Lord Arthur Hill]] | years=1886}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Parliamentary Secretary to the Treasury]] | before=[[Aretas Akers-Douglas, 1st Viscount Chilston|Aretas Akers-Douglas]] | after=[[Thomas Edward Ellis]] | years=1892\u20131894}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Lord Privy Seal]] | before=[[William Ewart Gladstone]] | after=[[R. A. Cross, 1st Viscount Cross|The Viscount Cross]] | years=1894\u20131895}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster]] | before=[[James Bryce, 1st Viscount Bryce|James Bryce]] | after=[[Henry James, 1st Baron James of Hereford|The Lord James of Hereford]] | years=1894\u20131895}}\n{{succession box | title=[[List of the First Lords of the Admiralty|First Lord of the Admiralty]] | before=[[Frederick Campbell, 3rd Earl Cawdor|The Earl Cawdor]] | after=[[Reginald McKenna]] | years=1905\u20131908}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Lord President of the Council]] | before=[[Robert Crewe-Milnes, 1st Marquess of Crewe|The Earl of Crewe]] | after=[[Henry Fowler, 1st Viscount Wolverhampton|The Viscount Wolverhampton]] | years=1908}}\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Baron Tweedmouth]]  | before=[[Dudley Marjoribanks, 1st Baron Tweedmouth|Dudley Coutts Marjoribanks]]  | after=[[Dudley Marjoribanks, 3rd Baron Tweedmouth|Dudley Churchill Marjoribanks]] | years=1894\u20131909}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n<!-- index House of Commons categories as Marjoribanks, because he held these before he inherited the peerage -->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tweedmouth, Edward Marjoribanks, 2nd Baron}}\n[[Category:1849 births]]\n[[Category:1909 deaths]]\n[[Category:Chancellors of the Duchy of Lancaster]]\n[[Category:Lord Presidents of the Council]]\n[[Category:Lords Privy Seal]]\n[[Category:First Lords of the Admiralty]]\n[[Category:Barons in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Thistle]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Scottish Liberal Party MPs|Marjoribanks, Edward]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Scottish constituencies|Marjoribanks, Edward]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1880\u20131885|Marjoribanks, Edward]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1885\u20131886|Marjoribanks, Edward]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1886\u20131892|Marjoribanks, Edward]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1892\u20131895|Marjoribanks, Edward]]\n[[Category:Progressive Party (London) politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of London County Council]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Christ Church, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Politicians awarded knighthoods]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people|Edward Marjoribanks}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Lord Tweedmouth\n| honorific-suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|KT|PC}}\n| image = Portrait of Edward Marjoribanks, 2nd Baron Tweedmouth.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption =\n\n| order1 = [[Lord President of the Council]]\n| term_start1 = 12 April 1908\n| term_end1 = 13 October 1908\n| monarch1 = [[Edward VII of the United Kingdom|Edward VII]]\n| primeminister1 = [[H. H. Asquith]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Robert Crewe-Milnes, 1st Marquess of Crewe|The Earl of Crewe]]\n| successor1 = [[Henry Fowler, 1st Viscount Wolverhampton|The Viscount Wolverhampton]]\n\n| order2 = [[List of the First Lords of the Admiralty|First Lord of the Admiralty]]\n| term_start2 = 10 December 1905\n| term_end2 = 12 April 1908\n| monarch2 = [[Edward VII of the United Kingdom|Edward VII]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Henry Campbell-Bannerman|Sir Henry Campbell-Bannerman]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Frederick Campbell, 3rd Earl Cawdor|The Earl Cawdor]]\n| successor2 = [[Reginald McKenna]]\n\n| order3 = [[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster]]\n| term_start3 = 28 May 1894\n| term_end3 = 21 June 1895\n| monarch3 = [[Victoria of the United Kingdom|Victoria]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery|The Earl of Rosebery]]\n| predecessor3 = [[James Bryce, 1st Viscount Bryce|James Bryce]]\n| successor3 = [[Henry James, 1st Baron James of Hereford|The Lord James of Hereford]]\n\n| order4 = [[Lord Privy Seal]]\n| term_start4 = 10 March 1894\n| term_end4 = 21 June 1895\n| monarch4 = [[Victoria of the United Kingdom|Victoria]]\n| primeminister4 = [[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery|The Earl of Rosebery]]\n| predecessor4 = [[William Ewart Gladstone]]\n| successor4 = [[R. A. Cross, 1st Viscount Cross|The Viscount Cross]]\n\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1849|7|8}}\n| birth_place =\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1909|9|15|1849|7|8}}\n| death_place =\n| nationality = British\n| party = [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]]\n| alma_mater =\n| spouse = {{marriage|Lady Fanny Spencer-Churchill (1853\u20131904)<br>|1873|1904|end=her death}}\n}}\n\n'''Edward Marjoribanks, 2nd Baron Tweedmouth''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|KT|PC}} (8 July 1849 \u2013 15 September 1909), was a moderate<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zrdjEV9zY5MC&pg=PA80&dq=tweedmouth%20moderate&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CD8Q6AEwBWoVChMIrfe5nfO8xwIViVjbCh1jDgEs#v=onepage&q=tweedmouth%20moderate&f=false|title=Defending the Empire: The Conservative Party and British Defence Policy, 1899-1915|first=Rhodri|last=Williams|date=1 January 1991|publisher=Yale University Press|accessdate=29 January 2017|via=Google Books}}</ref> British [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] statesman who sat in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] from 1880 until 1894 when he inherited his peerage and then sat in the [[House of Lords]]. He served in various capacities in the Liberal governments of the late 19th and early 20th centuries.\n\n==Biography==\nTweedmouth was the son of [[Dudley Marjoribanks, 1st Baron Tweedmouth]], and Isabella, daughter of [[Sir James Hogg, 1st Baronet]].<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p10633.htm|title=Person Page|publisher=|accessdate=29 January 2017}}</ref> [[Ishbel Hamilton-Gordon, Marchioness of Aberdeen and Temair]], was his sister. He is descended from Joseph Marjoribanks, a wine and fish merchant in Edinburgh who died in 1635 and is thought to have been the grandson of Thomas Marjoribanks of Ratho,<ref name = MBJournal3b>Marjoribanks, Roger. \"Marjoribanks of Lees\", [http://marjorib.awardspace.co.uk/JIssue3.html The Marjoribanks Journal Number 3], page 14, June 1995. Accessed on 22 May 2010</ref> head of the lowland [[Clan Marjoribanks]].<ref>[http://www.marjoribanks.net Clan Marjoribanks web site] accessed 29 April 2010.</ref> He was educated at [[Christ Church, Oxford]], but expelled in 1870 following a prank involving that led to the damage of college sculptures.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Curthoys |first1=Judith |title=Practical joke, or wanton vandalism? The Library Statues Row - May 1870 |url=https://www.chch.ox.ac.uk/blog/practical-joke-or-wanton-vandalism-library-statues-row-may-1870 |website=www.chch.ox.ac.uk |publisher=Christ Church, Oxford University |accessdate=2 May 2019}}</ref> \n\n===Political career===\n[[File:Edward Marjoribanks, 2nd Baron Tweedmouth.jpg|thumb|right|Tweedmouth]]\nTweedmouth was returned to Parliament for [[Berwickshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Berwickshire]] in 1880, a seat he held until 1894.<ref name=\"leighrayment\">{{cite web|url=http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Bcommons2.htm|publisher=leighrayment.com|title=House of Commons: Bedford to Berwick upon Tweed|accessdate=3 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224095640/http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Bcommons2.htm|archive-date=24 February 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> The seat had been held earlier in the century by his [[great-uncle]], [[Sir John Marjoribanks, 1st Baronet]] and cousin, [[Charles Albany Marjoribanks]].\n\nHe served under [[William Ewart Gladstone]] as [[Comptroller of the Household]] in between February and July 1886<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=25558 |date=12 February 1886 |page=682 }}</ref> and was sworn of the [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|Privy Council]] the same year.<ref name=\"leighrayment2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.leighrayment.com/pcouncil/pcouncil2.htm|publisher=leighrayment.com|title= Privy Counsellors: 1836\u20131914 |accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref> When the Liberals returned to power under Gladstone in 1892, he was made [[Parliamentary Secretary to the Treasury]] (chief whip).<ref name=\"leighrayment.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.leighrayment.com/peers/peersT2.htm|publisher=leighrayment.com|title= Peerage: Tiberris to Tyrrell |accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref> He succeeded his father in the barony in March 1894, only a few days before Gladstone resigned and [[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery|Lord Rosebery]] became Prime Minister. Rosebery appointed Tweedmouth [[Lord Privy Seal]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=26496 |date=20 March 1894 |page=1661 }}</ref> with a seat in the cabinet, and in May 1894 he also became [[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster]]. He retained these posts until the government fell in 1895.<ref name=\"leighrayment.com\"/>\n\nAfter ten years in opposition, the Liberals again came to power in December 1905 under [[Henry Campbell-Bannerman|Sir Henry Campbell-Bannerman]], who appointed Tweedmouth [[List of the First Lords of the Admiralty|First Lord of the Admiralty]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=27866 |date=22 December 1905 |page=9172 }}</ref> with a seat in the cabinet. In early 1908 he was criticised for corresponding with German emperor [[William II of Germany|William II]] on the British naval programme. The matter was referred to the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]]. [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] [[H. H. Asquith]] eventually stated that the correspondence was \"a purely personal and private communication, conceived in an entirely friendly spirit\" and no action was taken.<ref name=obit/>  However, when Asquith succeeded Campbell-Bannerman as Prime Minister in April 1908 Tweedmouth was removed as head of the Admiralty and became [[Lord President of the Council]].<ref name=\"leighrayment.com\"/> He suffered a nervous breakdown in June 1908, a condition which was said to partly explain his indiscretion in communicating with the German Emperor on naval matters. Although his health later recovered, he resigned in October 1908.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1908/09/29/archives/lord-tweedmouth-resigns-quits-presidency-of-the-council-but-his.html|title=LORD TWEEDMOUTH RESIGNS.; Quits Presidency of the Council, but His Mental Condition Is Improved.|date=29 September 1908|publisher=|accessdate=29 January 2017|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> He was made a [[Order of the Thistle|Knight of the Thistle]] in 1908.<ref name=\"leighrayment3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.leighrayment.com/orders/thistle.htm|publisher=leighrayment.com|title=Knights of the Thistle |accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nAn advocate of worker\u2019s rights<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ucd_AAAAQBAJ&pg=PT72&dq=Lord%20Tweedmouth%20eighty%20club%20speech%20working%20class&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCYQ6AEwAWoVChMI3MHHiJ3jxwIV65zbCh3zxgyO#v=onepage&q=Lord%20Tweedmouth%20eighty%20club%20speech%20working%20class&f=false|title=Edward Carpenter and Late Victorian Radicalism|first1=Tony|last1=Brown|first2=Thomas N.|last2=Corns|date=21 August 2013|publisher=Routledge|accessdate=29 January 2017|via=Google Books}}</ref> and social legislation,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/1905/may/09/workmens-compensation-bill-hl#S4V0145P0_19050509_HOL_105|title=WORKMEN'S COMPENSATION BILL [H.L.] (Hansard, 9 May 1905)|publisher=|accessdate=29 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/1901/mar/08/the-housing-problem-government-policy#S4V0090P0_19010308_HOL_53|title=THE HOUSING PROBLEM \u2014 GOVERNMENT POLICY. (Hansard, 8 March 1901)|publisher=|accessdate=29 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/1902/mar/13/factory-and-workshop-act-1901-amendment#S4V0104P0_19020313_HOL_31|title=FACTORY AND WORKSHOP ACT (1901) AMENDMENT BILL [H.L.] (Hansard, 13 March 1902)|publisher=|accessdate=29 January 2017}}</ref> Tweedmouth was supportive of the Liberal Party\u2019s alliance with the Labour Party in the lead-up to the 1906 General Election, believing that the Liberals could not win without it, and regarded as \u201chumbug\u201d the view that such an alliance meant class legislation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p9fTBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA167&dq=Lord%20Tweedmouth%20working%20class&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CDgQ6AEwBGoVChMIi_31np3jxwIVYoHbCh0HjAAf#v=onepage&q=Lord%20Tweedmouth%20working%20class&f=false|title=Liberal Hearts and Coronets: The Lives and Times of Ishbel Marjoribanks Gordon and John Campbell Gordon, the Aberdeens|first=Veronica|last=Strong-Boag|date=1 January 2015|publisher=University of Toronto Press|accessdate=29 January 2017|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nHe died on 15 September 1909.<ref name=obit>{{cite news |author= |title=Lord Tweedmouth Dead |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1909/09/16/archives/lord-tweedmouth-dead-his-correspondence-with-german-emperor-caused.html |quote= |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=16 September 1909 }}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nLord Tweedmouth married Lady Fanny Octavia Louise (1853\u20131904), daughter of [[John Spencer-Churchill, 7th Duke of Marlborough]] and aunt of [[Winston Churchill|Sir Winston Churchill]], in 1873. She reportedly died from cancer in August 1904, aged 51 \"at Lord Tweedmouth's Glen Affric shooting lodge\". They had a son and [[heir]]; [[Dudley Marjoribanks, 3rd Baron Tweedmouth|Dudley, 3rd Baron Tweedmouth]] (1874\u20131935).<ref>{{cite web|title=DEATH OF LADY TWEED MOUTH Lady Tweedmouth died last night at Lord Tweedmouth's shooting lodge, Glen Affric,  in Strathglass, Inverness-shire.|url=http://www.genesreunited.co.uk/searchbna/results?memberlastsubclass=none&searchhistorykey=0&keywords=lady%20tweedmouth%20glen%20affric%20lodge%20shooting&from=1875&to=1949|publisher=Edinburgh Evening News Midlothian, Scotland  |date= 6 August 1904|accessdate=13 January 2014|quote=DEATH OF LADY TWEED MOUTH Lady Tweed mouth died last night at Lord Tweedmouth's shooting lodge in Strathglass, Inverness-shire. Lady Fanny Occavia Louisa Spencer-Churchill was married to Lord Tweedmouth in 1873. She was the third daughter of the seventh Duke of.....}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=McCall|first1=Alison|title=Fanny Octavia Louisa Spencer-Churchill|url=http://womenofscotland.org.uk/women/fanny-octavia-louisa-spencer-churchill|date=6 April 2016|accessdate=29 January 2017|quote=She died of cancer in 1904}}</ref>\n\nLord Tweedmouth's parliamentary career saw him  reported as being the '''Laird of Guisachan and Glenaffric'''  who was, on occasions, \"in a fighting mood\".<ref>{{cite web|title=THE ABERDEEN JOURNAL, TUESDAY, NOVEMBER 22, 1898,|url=http://www.genesreunited.co.uk/searchbna/results?memberlastsubclass=none&searchhistorykey=0&keywords=laird%20tweedmouth%20glenaffric&from=1875&to=1949&page=4|publisher=Aberdeen Press and Journal Aberdeenshire, Scotland |date= 22 November 1898|accessdate=13 January 2015|quote= The laird of Guisachan and Glenaffric was in a fighting mood last night, and he devoted the main part of his address to an attack on Mr Chamberlain\u2019s Manchester speeches. Lord Tweedmouth does not affect the most...}}</ref>  Following Lady Tweedmouth's death, Lord Tweedmouth  sold the [[Laird]]ship of  [[Glen Affric]], the property including the Guisachan  Estate and deer park that his family had owned since the 1850s.<ref>{{cite web|title=ISHBEL LADY ABERDEEN AT INVERNESS|url=http://www.genesreunited.co.uk/searchbna/results?memberlastsubclass=none&searchhistorykey=0&keywords=lady%20of%20guisachan%20glen%20%20affric&from=1875&to=1949&page=1|publisher=The Scotsman Midlothian, Scotland |date= 14 December 1934|accessdate=29 January 2013|quote=....presided, spoke of Lady Aberdeen's connection with the Highlands and to the many happy days she spent in Glen Affric, which was then the property of her father. (i.e. Dudley Marjoribanks, 1st Baron Tweedmouth, died 1894)}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title=Golden Retriever | publisher=i5 Publishing | last=Pepper|first= Jeffrey G. | year=2012 | pages=27 | isbn=9781621870340}}</ref>  He was reported as being a \"generous [[laird]]\", who, like his father,  \"did much for the people\" of his estate; the \"ties which united the people of Glen Affric with the Laird and his lady were close\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000470/19080414/139/0006?_=1492211773772|work=The Berwickshire News|date=14 April 1908|page=6|title=The late Dowager Lady Tweedmouth|accessdate=15 April 2007|quote=Close were the ties which united the people of Glen Affric with the Laird and his lady. Secluded from the world...{{subscription required}}}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=ISHBEL, LADY ABERDEEN \u2014  The Home of Her Youth Revisited  - A HIGHLAND WELCOME|url=http://www.genesreunited.co.uk/searchbna/results?memberlastsubclass=none&searchhistorykey=0&keywords=laird%20and%20lady%20tweedmouth&from=1875&to=1949|publisher=The Scotsman Midlothian, Scotland |date= 15 December 1934|accessdate=13 January 2014|quote=Many present remembered Lady Aberdeen as the lovely daughter of Lord Tweedmouth, who, like his son who succeeded him, was a generous laird and did much for the estate.....and especially for the people of Guisachan}}</ref>\n\nLord Tweedmouth survived his wife by five years and died in September 1909, aged 60. He was succeeded in the barony by his son, [[Dudley Marjoribanks, 3rd Baron Tweedmouth|Dudley]].<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\"/>\n\n==The Rocking Chair Ranche==\nFrom 1883 until 1896, he was an owner of and investor in [[Rocking Chair Ranche]] located in [[Collingsworth County]], [[Texas]], along with his father, [[Dudley Marjoribanks, 1st Baron Tweedmouth|The 1st Baron Tweedmouth]], and his brother-in-law, [[John Hamilton-Gordon, 1st Marquess of Aberdeen and Temair|The 7th Earl of Aberdeen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/apr01|title=ROCKING CHAIR RANCH|first=Anderson H.|last=Allen|date=15 June 2010|publisher=|accessdate=29 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n;Secondary sources\n*{{cite book | editor-first=Charles | editor-last=Mosley | title=Burke's Peerage and Baronetage | place=London: The Boydell Press | date=2003 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Edward Marjoribanks, 2nd Baron Tweedmouth}}\n* {{Cite DNB|wstitle=Marjoribanks, Edward |short=x}}\n* {{hansard-contribs | mr-edward-marjoribanks | Edward Marjoribanks, 2nd Baron Tweedmouth }}\n* {{NPG name}}\n*[http://www.vandaprints.com/image.php?id=142557 Photograph of Lord Tweedmouth at vandaprints.com]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box | title=Member of Parliament for [[Berwickshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Berwickshire]] | before=[[Robert Baillie-Hamilton|Hon. Robert Baillie-Hamilton]] | after=[[Harold Tennant]] | years=1880\u20131894}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Comptroller of the Household]] | before=[[Lord Arthur Hill]] | after=[[Lord Arthur Hill]] | years=1886}}\