 for Scottish constituencies|Marjoribanks, Edward]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1880\u20131885|Marjoribanks, Edward]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1885\u20131886|Marjoribanks, Edward]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1886\u20131892|Marjoribanks, Edward]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1892\u20131895|Marjoribanks, Edward]]\n[[Category:Progressive Party (London) politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of London County Council]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Christ Church, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Politicians awarded knighthoods]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePolitical career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Marjoribanks,_2nd_Baron_Tweedmouth"}
{"title_page": "Sir Frederick Mappin, 1st Baronet", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2017}}\n[[File:Sir_Frederick_Mappin.jpg|thumb|right|Sir Frederick Mappin]][[File:F C Mappin 2730.jpg|thumb|right|Sir Frederick Thorpe Mappin, Portrait in Mappin Hall, University of Sheffield]]\n'''Sir Frederick Thorpe Mappin, 1st Baronet''', known as '''Frederick Mappin''' (16 May 1821 \u2013 19 March 1910) was an English factory owner and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] [[politician]].\n\nBorn in [[Sheffield]], Mappin worked for his father's [[cutlery]] company from the age of thirteen, running it alone after his father's death in 1841.  In 1851, he became the youngest ever [[Master Cutler]], but after a dispute with his younger brother, he left the firm, which later became part of [[Mappin and Webb]].\n\nMappin then bought a [[steelworks]] and implemented machine working, despite a [[Strike action|strike]] by employees. In 1854, he was elected to [[Sheffield City Council|Sheffield Town Council]] as a [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]], stepping down in 1857. In the 1860s, Mappin became a director of the [[Sheffield Gas and Light Company]], and of the [[Midland Railway]]. In 1865 Mappin moved into [[Thornbury Hospital|Thornbury]], a new country house he had built in [[Ranmoor]], now a Sheffield suburb.\n\nIn 1876, Mappin was re-elected to the Town Council, and served as the [[Lord Mayor of Sheffield|Mayor of Sheffield]] in 1877\u201378.  In 1878, he was a juror at the [[Paris Universal Exhibition]], and was awarded the [[L\u00e9gion d'honneur]].  At the [[1880 United Kingdom general election|1880 general election]], he was elected as [[Member of Parliament]] for [[East Retford (UK Parliament constituency)|East Retford]], while remaining on Sheffield Town Council until 1883. Mappin was a major supporter of the creation of the [[Sheffield Central Technical School]].\n\nUnder the [[Redistribution of Seats Act 1885]], Mappin's Parliamentary seat was abolished, and he moved instead to represent [[Hallamshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Hallamshire]], a post he held until 1905.  That year, he supported the formation of the [[University of Sheffield]], and was created its first Pro-Chancellor.  The University's [[Sir Frederick Mappin Building]] is named after him.\n\nHe was appointed an honorary [[Freedom of the City|Freeman]] of the City of [[Sheffield]] in 1900.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Lord Kitchener at Sheffield|day_of_week=Wednesday |date=1 October 1902 |page_number=9 |issue=36887| }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n*\"Mappin, Sir Frederick Thorpe\", ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]''\n*\"[http://www.made-in-sheffield.com/People/frederickThorpeMappin.htm Sir Frederick Thorpe Mappin]\", Made in Sheffield\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | sir-frederick-mappin | Sir Frederick Mappin }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par |uk}}\n{{s-bef |before=[[William Beckett-Denison]]\n        |before2=[[Francis Foljambe (Liberal politician)|Francis Foljambe]]}}\n{{s-ttl |title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[East Retford (UK Parliament constituency)|East Retford]]\n        |years=1880\u20131885\n        |with=[[Francis Foljambe (Liberal politician)|Francis Foljambe]]}}\n{{s-non |reason=Constituency abolished}}\n{{s-new |constituency}}\n{{s-ttl |title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Hallamshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Hallamshire]]\n        |years=1885\u20131905}}\n{{s-aft |after=[[John Wadsworth]]}}\n{{s-bef |before=[[Spencer Charrington]]}}\n{{s-ttl |title=Oldest [[Member of Parliament]] |years=1904\u20131905}}\n{{s-aft |after=[[Samuel Young (Irish politician)|Samuel Young]]}}\n\n{{s-reg |uk-bt}}\n{{s-new |creation}}\n{{s-ttl |title=[[Mappin baronets|Baronet]]<br>'''(of Thornbury)''' |years=1886\u20131910}}\n{{s-aft |after=[[Sir Frank Mappin, 2nd Baronet|Frank Mappin]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mappin, Frederick}}\n[[Category:1821 births]]\n[[Category:1910 deaths]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Yorkshire and the Humber]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Honour]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Lord Mayors of Sheffield]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1880\u20131885]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1885\u20131886]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1886\u20131892]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1892\u20131895]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1895\u20131900]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1900\u20131906]]\n[[Category:Master Cutlers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2017}}\n[[File:Sir_Frederick_Mappin.jpg|thumb|right|Sir Frederick Mappin]][[File:F C Mappin 2730.jpg|thumb|right|Sir Frederick Thorpe Mappin, Portrait in Mappin Hall, University of Sheffield]]\n'''Sir Frederick Thorpe Mappin, 1st Baronet''', known as '''Frederick Mappin''' (16 May 1821 \u2013 19 March 1910) was an English factory owner and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] [[politician]].\n\nBorn in [[Sheffield]], Mappin worked for his father's [[cutlery]] company from the age of thirteen, running it alone after his father's death in 1841.  In 1851, he became the youngest ever [[Master Cutler]], but after a dispute with his younger brother, he left the firm, which later became part of [[Mappin and Webb]].\n\nMappin then bought a [[steelworks]] and implemented machine working, despite a [[Strike action|strike]] by employees. In 1854, he was elected to [[Sheffield City Council|Sheffield Town Council]] as a [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]], stepping down in 1857. In the 1860s, Mappin became a director of the [[Sheffield Gas and Light Company]], and of the [[Midland Railway]]. In 1865 Mappin moved into [[Thornbury Hospital|Thornbury]], a new country house he had built in [[Ranmoor]], now a Sheffield suburb.\n\nIn 1876, Mappin was re-elected to the Town Council, and served as the [[Lord Mayor of Sheffield|Mayor of Sheffield]] in 1877-78.  In 1878, he was a juror at the [[Paris Universal Exhibition]], and was awarded the [[L\u00e9gion d'honneur]].  At the [[1880 United Kingdom general election|1880 general election]], he was elected as [[Member of Parliament]] for [[East Retford (UK Parliament constituency)|East Retford]], while remaining on Sheffield Town Council until 1883. Mappin was a major supporter of the creation of the [[Sheffield Central Technical School]].\n\nUnder the [[Redistribution of Seats Act 1885]], Mappin's Parliamentary seat was abolished, and he moved instead to represent [[Hallamshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Hallamshire]], a post he held until 1905.  That year, he supported the formation of the [[University of Sheffield]], and was created its first Pro-Chancellor.  The University's [[Sir Frederick Mappin Building]] is named after him.\n\nHe was appointed an honorary [[Freedom of the City|Freeman]] of the City of [[Sheffield]] in 1900.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Lord Kitchener at Sheffield|day_of_week=Wednesday |date=1 October 1902 |page_number=9 |issue=36887| }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n*\"Mappin, Sir Frederick Thorpe\", ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]''\n*\"[http://www.made-in-sheffield.com/People/frederickThorpeMappin.htm Sir Frederick Thorpe Mappin]\", Made in Sheffield\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | sir-frederick-mappin | Sir Frederick Mappin }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par |uk}}\n{{s-bef |before=[[William Beckett-Denison]]\n        |before2=[[Francis Foljambe (Liberal politician)|Francis Foljambe]]}}\n{{s-ttl |title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[East Retford (UK Parliament constituency)|East Retford]]\n        |years=1880\u20131885\n        |with=[[Francis Foljambe (Liberal politician)|Francis Foljambe]]}}\n{{s-non |reason=Constituency abolished}}\n{{s-new |constituency}}\n{{s-ttl |title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Hallamshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Hallamshire]]\n        |years=1885\u20131905}}\n{{s-aft |after=[[John Wadsworth]]}}\n{{s-bef |before=[[Spencer Charrington]]}}\n{{s-ttl |title=Oldest [[Member of Parliament]] |years=1904\u20131905}}\n{{s-aft |after=[[Samuel Young (Irish politician)|Samuel Young]]}}\n\n{{s-reg |uk-bt}}\n{{s-new |creation}}\n{{s-ttl |title=[[Mappin baronets|Baronet]]<br>'''(of Thornbury)''' |years=1886\u20131910}}\n{{s-aft |after=[[Sir Frank Mappin, 2nd Baronet|Frank Mappin]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mappin, Frederick}}\n[[Category:1821 births]]\n[[Category:1910 deaths]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Yorkshire and the Humber]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Honour]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Lord Mayors of Sheffield]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1880\u20131885]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1885\u20131886]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1886\u20131892]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1892\u20131895]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1895\u20131900]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1900\u20131906]]\n[[Category:Master Cutlers]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1877-78 \u2192 1877\u201378", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sir_Frederick_Mappin,_1st_Baronet"}
{"title_page": "2019 UNC Wilmington Seahawks men's soccer team", "text_new": "#REDIRECT [[UNC Wilmington Seahawks men's soccer]]\n\n[[Category:UNC Wilmington Seahawks men's soccer seasons|2019]]\n[[Category:2019 Colonial Athletic Association men's soccer season|UNC Wilmington Seahawks]]\n[[Category:American men's college soccer teams 2019 season|UNC Wilmington Seahawks]]\n[[Category:2019 in sports in North Carolina|UNC Wilmington Seahawks men's soccer]]\n", "text_old": "#REDIRECT [[UNC Wilmington Seahawks men's soccer]]\n\n[[Category:UNC Wilmington Seahawks men's soccer seasons]]\n[[Category:2019 Colonial Athletic Association men's soccer season|UNC Wilmington Seahawks]]\n[[Category:American men's college soccer teams 2019 season|UNC Wilmington Seahawks]]\n[[Category:2019 in sports in North Carolina|UNC Wilmington Seahawks men's soccer]]\n", "name_user": "18pittsone", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=2019_UNC_Wilmington_Seahawks_men%27s_soccer_team&redirect=no"}
{"title_page": "Sir Trevor Lawrence, 2nd Baronet", "text_new": "{{for|the American football player|Trevor Lawrence (American football)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = Sir\n| name               = Trevor Lawrence\n| honorific_suffix   = KCVO KStJ\n| image              = Trevor_Lawrence_GC_1913.jpg\n| birth_name         = James John Trevor Lawrence\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1831|12|30}}\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1913|12|22|1831|12|20}}\n| death_place        = Burford Lodge, [[Dorking]], [[Surrey]]\n| resting_place      = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| burial_place       = \n| burial_coordinates = \n| nationality        = British\n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = [[Winchester College]] <br>[[St Bartholomew's Hospital]]\n| occupation         = Surgeon, politician, horticulturalist\n| spouse             = Elizabeth Matthew\n| children           = [[Sir William Lawrence, 3rd Baronet|William Matthew Trevor Lawrence]], <br>[[Aubrey Lawrence|Aubrey Trevor Lawrence]], <br>Charles Trevor Lawrence, <br>Bessie Mary Lawrence\n| mother             = [[Louisa Lawrence|Louisa Senior]]\n| father             = [[Sir William Lawrence, 1st Baronet|Sir William Lawrence]]\n}}\n\n'''Sir James John Trevor Lawrence 2nd Baronet''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|KCVO|KStJ}} (30 December 1831 \u2013 22 December 1913), known as '''Sir Trevor Lawrence''', was an [[United Kingdom|English]] surgeon, [[Horticulture|horticulturalist]] and [[works of art|art]] collector. He later became a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament (UK)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for 17 years, retiring to become treasurer of [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]] where he founded the '''Lawrence Scholarship''' and contributed to the [[King's Fund|King Edward's Hospital Fund]].  \n\n[[Image:Sir Trevor Lawrence.JPG|thumb|right|Caricature of Sir Trevor Lawrence by SPY ([[Sir Leslie Ward]]), Vanity Fair, 1899]]\nDuring his time as MP he became president of the [[Royal Horticultural Society]] serving 28 years until death, overseeing a growth in interest in membership and horticulture in general across the British Empire.  He is the inspiration for a hybrid [[Iris (plant)|Aril Iris]], ''Iris Sir Trevor Lawrence'' and a genus of orchids, ''[[Trevoria]]''.  The society also founded a gold medal in his honour.\n\n==Childhood and early adulthood==\n[[Image:The_Burford_Bridge_Hotel_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1356677.jpg|thumb|Burford Bridge Hotel, extended by the family]]\nLawrence was born on 30 December 1831, the son of [[Sir William Lawrence, 1st Baronet|Sir William Lawrence]] and [[Louisa Lawrence|Louisa Senior]], the daughter of a successful [[Mayfair]] [[haberdasher]] who had bought a country estate, Broughton House, near [[Aylesbury]], [[Buckinghamshire]]. {{refn|He was christened in April 1883 at [[St Martin-in-the-Fields]], Westminster.|group=note}} He was educated at [[Winchester College]] and at [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]], where he took the diploma of [[Membership of the Royal College of Surgeons|MRCS]] in 1853. He then worked for nearly ten years for the [[Indian Medical Service]]. Having inherited his mother's particular love for orchids, he reinforced this when he was in [[India]]. He made his first collection when living at [[Dharamsala, Himachal Pradesh|Dharamsala]] in the [[Himalayas|Himalayan]] foothills.\n\nOn 5 July 1867, Lawrence succeeded to his father's recently created baronetcy (see [[Lawrence Baronets]]). In 1869 he married Elizabeth, daughter of John Matthew, a partner in the leading firm of marine engineers, [[John Penn (engineer)|John Penn and Son]] of [[Greenwich]]. She inherited Burford Lodge, [[Dorking]], where they created a celebrated garden at the foot of [[Box Hill, Surrey|Box Hill]].{{refn|At the time, the Burford Lodge estate  included the [[Burford Bridge Hotel]].|group=note}} They had three sons and one daughter:\n*[[Sir William Lawrence, 3rd Baronet|William Matthew Trevor Lawrence]] (17 September 1870 \u2013 4 January 1934); married Iris [[Eyre Crabbe]] (1908) and had issue.\n*[[Aubrey Lawrence|Aubrey Trevor Lawrence]] (15 January 1879 \u2013 23 March 1930); married Constance Emily Fanning McGaw (1901) and had issue.\n*Charles Trevor Lawrence (18 September 1881 \u2013 10 April 1953); married Adeliza Donnelly (1916).\n*Bessie Mary Lawrence (11 November 1877 - 12 March 1944); married Henry Rottenburg (1911) and had issue.\n\n==Political career==\nIn 1874 he unsuccessfully contested [[Gloucester (UK Parliament constituency)|Gloucester]] as a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]], but in 1875 was elected for [[Mid Surrey (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid-Surrey]], which included a large portion of south [[London]]. He sat for that constituency for ten years until its abolition in the [[Redistribution of Seats Act 1885|redistribution of seats in 1885]], when he was elected for [[Reigate (UK Parliament constituency)|Reigate Division]] in [[Surrey]], a seat he held for seven years. He did not seek re-election at the 1892 general elections. He confined himself in parliament largely to questions and speeches on constituency matters (such as the abolition of tolls on bridges over the [[River Thames]]) and matters of [[public health]] (he was a strong supporter of [[vaccination]]).  He made 20 contributions reaching Hansard, spanning 1886-8 and 1892.\n\n==Horticulture==\nLawrence's chief interest, however, was horticulture, an interest he had inherited from his mother, herself a horticulturalist of note. From 1885 to 1913 he was President of the [[Royal Horticultural Society]] (RHS) which increased greatly in numbers and means during this term. He was determined that it should be restored \u201cto horticulture pure and simple,\u201d rather than entertaining the public. He was chiefly responsible for moving the Society from its expensive [[Kensington]] site to a more practical home in [[Westminster]] in 1904. The society presented him with the [[Victoria Medal of Honour|Victoria Medal]] in 1900, a portrait painted by [[Hubert von Herkomer|Sir Hubert Herkomer]] in 1906, and the [[The Veitch Memorial Medal|Veitch Gold Memorial Medal]] 1913; it also founded the Lawrence Gold Medal in his honour.\n\nHe was one of the world's leading [[Orchidaceae|orchid]] collectors and asked his wife to give plants of botanical interest to [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew|Kew]] after his death: 580 were thought to qualify. He presided at the RHS conference on [[Hybrid (biology)|hybrid]]isation in 1899, which is now officially regarded as the first international conference on [[genetics]].\n\nIn 1905, [[Michael Foster (physiologist)|Professor M. Foster]] named a hybrid [[Iris (plant)|Aril Iris]] after him, a cross between ''[[Iris iberica]]'' X ''[[Iris pallida]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Arilbred Iris (Iris 'Sir Trevor Lawrence') in the Irises Database |url=http://garden.org/plants/view/603625/Arilbred-Iris-Iris-Sir-Trevor-Lawrence/ |publisher=garden.org |accessdate=24 November 2016}}</ref> Also ''[[Clematis texensis]]'' 'Sir Trevor Lawrence', [[Tulipa]] 'Sir Trevor Lawrence' and [[Begonia]] were also named after him.  A genus of orchids, ''[[Trevoria]]'', bears his name as well.<ref>{{cite web |title=Searching the NGA's Plant Database |url=http://garden.org/plants/search/text/?q=Sir+Trevor+Lawrence |publisher=garden.org |accessdate=24 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Hospital body contributions==\nIn 1892 he succeeded [[Sir Sydney Waterlow, 1st Baronet|Sir Sydney Waterlow]] as treasurer of [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]] and held that office for twelve years. In that time he founded the Lawrence Scholarship in memory of his father and was a member of the Council of [[King's Fund|King Edward's Hospital Fund]] also making donations. He was created a Knight Commander of the [[Royal Victorian Order]] (KCVO) in the November [[1902 Birthday Honours]] list,<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Birthday Honours |day_of_week=Monday |date=10 November 1902 |page_number=10 |issue=36921| }}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=27493 |date=7 November 1902 |pages=7161\u20137163  |supp=y}}</ref> and was also a [[Venerable Order of Saint John|Knight of Grace of the Order of St John of Jerusalem]].\n\n==Artworks legacy==\nHe was a well-known collector of [[work of art|objets d'art]], particularly oriental, especially Japanese, art, western [[porcelain]], and old [[lace]]. Some of his collector's items are now in the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]] and other museums.\n\n==Death==\nHe died at Burford Lodge. His will was sworn in 1914 at {{GBP|13580|1914|round=-5|about=yes|long=no}}.<ref>https://probatesearch.service.gov.uk Calendar of Probates and Administrations</ref>\n\n\n==See also==\n*[[Lawrence Baronets]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*Boyle, Frederick. About Orchids: A Chat. 1893.\n*Elliott, Brent. History of the Royal Horticultural Society 1804\u20132004. London: Phillimore, 2004\n*Kidd, Charles, Williamson, David (editors). ''Debrett's Peerage and Baronetage'' (1990 edition). New York: St Martin's Press, 1990, {{Page needed |date=February 2013}}\n*{{Rayment-bt|date=March 2012}}\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n*''Burkes Peerage and Baronetage'' (2003), s.v. Lawrence, Baronets, of Ealing Park\n*''http://livesonline.rcseng.ac.uk/biogs/E000014b.htm''\n*{{cite journal | pmc=2300350 | year=1914 | title=SIR TREVOR LAWRENCE, Bart., K.C.V.O., M.R.C.S | journal=British Medical Journal | volume=1 | issue=2767 | pages=121\u2013122 | doi=10.1136/bmj.1.2767.121}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | sir-james-lawrence-1 | Sir Trevor Lawrence }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Sir Henry Peek, 1st Baronet|Sir Henry Peek, Bt.]]<br />[[Richard Baggallay]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Mid Surrey (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Surrey]]\n | years = [[1875 East Suffolk by-election|1875]]\u2013[[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885]]\n | with  = [[Sir Henry Peek, 1st Baronet|Sir Henry Peek, Bt.]] to 1874\n | with2 = [[Sir John Ellis, 1st Baronet|Sir John Ellis, Bt.]] from 1874\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = Constituency abolished }}\n{{s-new | constituency}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Reigate (UK Parliament constituency)|Reigate]]\n | years = [[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885]]\u2013[[1892 United Kingdom general election|1892]]\n}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Henry Cubitt, 2nd Baron Ashcombe|Henry Cubitt]] }}\n{{s-reg|uk-bt}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Lawrence Baronets|Baronet]]<br/>'''(of Ealing Park)'''\n | years  = 1867\u20131913\n | before = [[Sir William Lawrence, 1st Baronet|William Lawrence]]\n | after  = [[Sir William Lawrence, 3rd Baronet|William Matthew Trevor Lawrence]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lawrence, Trevor}}\n[[Category:1831 births]]\n[[Category:1913 deaths]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:People educated at Winchester College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1880\u20131885]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1885\u20131886]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1886\u20131892]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Indian Medical Service officers]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the American football player|Trevor Lawrence (American football)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = Sir\n| name               = Trevor Lawrence\n| honorific_suffix   = KCVO KStJ\n| image              = Trevor_Lawrence_GC_1913.jpg\n| birth_name         = James John Trevor Lawrence\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1831|12|30}}\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1913|12|22|1831|12|20}}\n| death_place        = Burford Lodge, [[Dorking]], [[Surrey]]\n| resting_place      = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| burial_place       = \n| burial_coordinates = \n| nationality        = British\n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = [[Winchester College]] <br>[[St Bartholomew's Hospital]]\n| occupation         = Surgeon, politician, horticulturalist\n| spouse             = Elizabeth Matthew\n| children           = [[Sir William Lawrence, 3rd Baronet|William Matthew Trevor Lawrence]], <br>[[Aubrey Lawrence|Aubrey Trevor Lawrence]], <br>Charles Trevor Lawrence, <br>Bessie Mary Lawrence\n| mother             = [[Louisa Lawrence|Louisa Senior]]\n| father             = [[Sir William Lawrence, 1st Baronet|Sir William Lawrence]]\n}}\n\n'''Sir James John Trevor Lawrence 2nd Baronet''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|KCVO|KStJ}} (30 December 1831 \u2013 22 December 1913), known as '''Sir Trevor Lawrence''', was an [[United Kingdom|English]] surgeon, [[Horticulture|horticulturalist]] and [[works of art|art]] collector. He later became a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament (UK)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for 17 years, retiring to become treasurer of [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]] where he founded the '''Lawrence Scholarship''' and contributed to the [[King's Fund|King Edward's Hospital Fund]].  \n\n[[Image:Sir Trevor Lawrence.JPG|thumb|right|Caricature of Sir Trevor Lawrence by SPY ([[Sir Leslie Ward]]), Vanity Fair, 1899]]\nDuring his time as MP he became president of the [[Royal Horticultural Society]] serving 28 years until death, overseeing a growth in interest in membership and horticulture in general across the British Empire.  He is the inspiration for a hybrid [[Iris (plant)|Aril Iris]], ''Iris Sir Trevor Lawrence'' and a genus of orchids, ''[[Trevoria]]''.  The society also founded a gold medal in his honour.\n\n==Childhood and early adulthood==\n[[Image:The_Burford_Bridge_Hotel_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1356677.jpg|thumb|Burford Bridge Hotel, extended by the family]]\nLawrence was born on 30 December 1831, the son of [[Sir William Lawrence, 1st Baronet|Sir William Lawrence]] and [[Louisa Lawrence|Louisa Senior]], the daughter of a successful [[Mayfair]] [[haberdasher]] who had bought a country estate, Broughton House, near [[Aylesbury]], [[Buckinghamshire]]. {{refn|He was christened in April 1883 at [[St Martin-in-the-Fields]], Westminster.|group=note}} He was educated at [[Winchester College]] and at [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]], where he took the diploma of [[Membership of the Royal College of Surgeons|MRCS]] in 1853. He then worked for nearly ten years for the [[Indian Medical Service]]. Having inherited his mother\u2019s particular love for orchids, he reinforced this when he was in [[India]]. He made his first collection when living at [[Dharamsala, Himachal Pradesh|Dharamsala]] in the [[Himalayas|Himalayan]] foothills.\n\nOn 5 July 1867, Lawrence succeeded to his father's recently created baronetcy (see [[Lawrence Baronets]]). In 1869 he married Elizabeth, daughter of John Matthew, a partner in the leading firm of marine engineers, [[John Penn (engineer)|John Penn and Son]] of [[Greenwich]]. She inherited Burford Lodge, [[Dorking]], where they created a celebrated garden at the foot of [[Box Hill, Surrey|Box Hill]].{{refn|At the time, the Burford Lodge estate  included the [[Burford Bridge Hotel]].|group=note}} They had three sons and one daughter:\n*[[Sir William Lawrence, 3rd Baronet|William Matthew Trevor Lawrence]] (17 September 1870 \u2013 4 January 1934); married Iris [[Eyre Crabbe]] (1908) and had issue.\n*[[Aubrey Lawrence|Aubrey Trevor Lawrence]] (15 January 1879 \u2013 23 March 1930); married Constance Emily Fanning McGaw (1901) and had issue.\n*Charles Trevor Lawrence (18 September 1881 \u2013 10 April 1953); married Adeliza Donnelly (1916).\n*Bessie Mary Lawrence (11 November 1877 - 12 March 1944); married Henry Rottenburg (1911) and had issue.\n\n==Political career==\nIn 1874 he unsuccessfully contested [[Gloucester (UK Parliament constituency)|Gloucester]] as a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]], but in 1875 was elected for [[Mid Surrey (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid-Surrey]], which included a large portion of south [[London]]. He sat for that constituency for ten years until its abolition in the [[Redistribution of Seats Act 1885|redistribution of seats in 1885]], when he was elected for [[Reigate (UK Parliament constituency)|Reigate Division]] in [[Surrey]], a seat he held for seven years. He did not seek re-election at the 1892 general elections. He confined himself in parliament largely to questions and speeches on constituency matters (such as the abolition of tolls on bridges over the [[River Thames]]) and matters of [[public health]] (he was a strong supporter of [[vaccination]]).  He made 20 contributions reaching Hansard, spanning 1886-8 and 1892.\n\n==Horticulture==\nLawrence's chief interest, however, was horticulture, an interest he had inherited from his mother, herself a horticulturalist of note. From 1885 to 1913 he was President of the [[Royal Horticultural Society]] (RHS) which increased greatly in numbers and means during this term. He was determined that it should be restored \u201cto horticulture pure and simple,\u201d rather than entertaining the public. He was chiefly responsible for moving the Society from its expensive [[Kensington]] site to a more practical home in [[Westminster]] in 1904. The society presented him with the [[Victoria Medal of Honour|Victoria Medal]] in 1900, a portrait painted by [[Hubert von Herkomer|Sir Hubert Herkomer]] in 1906, and the [[The Veitch Memorial Medal|Veitch Gold Memorial Medal]] 1913; it also founded the Lawrence Gold Medal in his honour.\n\nHe was one of the world's leading [[Orchidaceae|orchid]] collectors and asked his wife to give plants of botanical interest to [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew|Kew]] after his death: 580 were thought to qualify. He presided at the RHS conference on [[Hybrid (biology)|hybrid]]isation in 1899, which is now officially regarded as the first international conference on [[genetics]].\n\nIn 1905, [[Michael Foster (physiologist)|Professor M. Foster]] named a hybrid [[Iris (plant)|Aril Iris]] after him, a cross between ''[[Iris iberica]]'' X ''[[Iris pallida]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Arilbred Iris (Iris 'Sir Trevor Lawrence') in the Irises Database |url=http://garden.org/plants/view/603625/Arilbred-Iris-Iris-Sir-Trevor-Lawrence/ |publisher=garden.org |accessdate=24 November 2016}}</ref> Also ''[[Clematis texensis]]'' 'Sir Trevor Lawrence', [[Tulipa]] 'Sir Trevor Lawrence' and [[Begonia]] were also named after him.  A genus of orchids, ''[[Trevoria]]'', bears his name as well.<ref>{{cite web |title=Searching the NGA's Plant Database |url=http://garden.org/plants/search/text/?q=Sir+Trevor+Lawrence |publisher=garden.org |accessdate=24 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Hospital body contributions==\nIn 1892 he succeeded [[Sir Sydney Waterlow, 1st Baronet|Sir Sydney Waterlow]] as treasurer of [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]] and held that office for twelve years. In that time he founded the Lawrence Scholarship in memory of his father and was a member of the Council of [[King's Fund|King Edward's Hospital Fund]] also making donations. He was created a Knight Commander of the [[Royal Victorian Order]] (KCVO) in the November [[1902 Birthday Honours]] list,<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Birthday Honours |day_of_week=Monday |date=10 November 1902 |page_number=10 |issue=36921| }}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=27493 |date=7 November 1902 |pages=7161\u20137163  |supp=y}}</ref> and was also a [[Venerable Order of Saint John|Knight of Grace of the Order of St John of Jerusalem]].\n\n==Artworks legacy==\nHe was a well-known collector of [[work of art|objets d'art]], particularly oriental, especially Japanese, art, western [[porcelain]], and old [[lace]]. Some of his collector's items are now in the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]] and other museums.\n\n==Death==\nHe died at Burford Lodge. His will was sworn in 1914 at {{GBP|13580|1914|round=-5|about=yes|long=no}}.<ref>https://probatesearch.service.gov.uk Calendar of Probates and Administrations</ref>\n\n\n==See also==\n*[[Lawrence Baronets]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*Boyle, Frederick. About Orchids: A Chat. 1893.\n*Elliott, Brent. History of the Royal Horticultural Society 1804-2004. London: Phillimore, 2004\n*Kidd, Charles, Williamson, David (editors). ''Debrett's Peerage and Baronetage'' (1990 edition). New York: St Martin's Press, 1990, {{Page needed |date=February 2013}}\n*{{Rayment-bt|date=March 2012}}\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n*''Burkes Peerage and Baronetage'' (2003), s.v. Lawrence, Baronets, of Ealing Park\n*''http://livesonline.rcseng.ac.uk/biogs/E000014b.htm''\n*{{cite journal | pmc=2300350 | year=1914 | title=SIR TREVOR LAWRENCE, Bart., K.C.V.O., M.R.C.S | journal=British Medical Journal | volume=1 | issue=2767 | pages=121\u2013122 | doi=10.1136/bmj.1.2767.121}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | sir-james-lawrence-1 | Sir Trevor Lawrence }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Sir Henry Peek, 1st Baronet|Sir Henry Peek, Bt.]]<br />[[Richard Baggallay]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Mid Surrey (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Surrey]]\n | years = [[1875 East Suffolk by-election|1875]]\u2013[[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885]]\n | with  = [[Sir Henry Peek, 1st Baronet|Sir Henry Peek, Bt.]] to 1874\n | with2 = [[Sir John Ellis, 1st Baronet|Sir John Ellis, Bt.]] from 1874\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = Constituency abolished }}\n{{s-new | constituency}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Reigate (UK Parliament constituency)|Reigate]]\n | years = [[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885]]\u2013[[1892 United Kingdom general election|1892]]\n}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Henry Cubitt, 2nd Baron Ashcombe|Henry Cubitt]] }}\n{{s-reg|uk-bt}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Lawrence Baronets|Baronet]]<br/>'''(of Ealing Park)'''\n | years  = 1867\u20131913\n | before = [[Sir William Lawrence, 1st Baronet|William Lawrence]]\n | after  = [[Sir William Lawrence, 3rd Baronet|William Matthew Trevor Lawrence]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lawrence, Trevor}}\n[[Category:1831 births]]\n[[Category:1913 deaths]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:People educated at Winchester College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1880\u20131885]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1885\u20131886]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1886\u20131892]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Indian Medical Service officers]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's, 1804-2004 \u2192 1804\u20132004", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sir_Trevor_Lawrence,_2nd_Baronet"}
{"title_page": "1908\u201309 British Home Championship", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox international football competition\n|tourney_name=1908\u20131909 British Home Championship\n|image      =\n|size       =\n|caption    =\n|country    =England, Ireland, Scotland and Wales\n|dates      =13 February\u20133 April 1909\n|num_teams  =4\n|champion   =ENG\n|count      =10\n|second     =WAL\n|attendance =\n|matches    =6\n|goals      =23\n|top_scorer =7 Players {{nowrap|(2 goals)}}\n|prevseason =[[1907\u201308_British_Home_Championship|1907\u201308]]\n|nextseason =[[1909\u201310_British_Home_Championship|1909\u201310]]\n}}\nThe '''1908\u201309 [[British Home Championship]]''' was an international [[football (soccer)|football]] tournament between the British [[Home Nations]]. [[England national football team|England]] dominated the competition with three wins over their opponents. When placed in the context of their overseas tours to Europe in [[1907\u201308 in English football#National team|1908]] and [[1908\u201309 in English football#National team|1909]], this made a run of ten victories for the English side led by prolific goalscorer [[Vivian Woodward]]. [[Wales national football team|Wales]], who were enjoying one of their most successful periods of international football, came second with two victories and [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] finished third. [[Ireland national football team (1882\u20131950)|Ireland]] finished last with no points and only two goals.\n\nEngland and Ireland began the tournament with England starting well, scoring four without reply. Wales and Scotland began their competition in March, the Welsh winning a close game in [[Wrexham]] 3\u20132. Scotland's response was a 5\u20130 thumping of the Irish in a strong display of goalscoring ability. England reaffirmed their position as favourites with a 2\u20130 win over Wales before Wales too made a final push for the title, becoming the only team in this edition of the tournament to win a match away, beating Ireland 3\u20132 in [[Belfast]]. In the final game, England needed only a draw to win the trophy undisputed. In the event they did better, scoring twice against Scotland without reply to take the trophy.\n\n==Table==\n<onlyinclude>{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|show_positions=n\n|winpoints=2\n\n|team1=ENG|name_ENG={{fb|ENG}}\n|team2=WAL|name_WAL={{fb|WAL|1807}}\n|team3=SCO|name_SCO={{fb|SCO}}\n|team4=IRE|name_IRE={{fb|IRE}}\n|win_ENG=3|draw_ENG=0|loss_ENG=0|gf_ENG=8|ga_ENG=0|status_ENG=C\n|win_WAL=2|draw_WAL=0|loss_WAL=1|gf_WAL=6|ga_WAL=6\n|win_SCO=1|draw_SCO=0|loss_SCO=2|gf_SCO=7|ga_SCO=5\n|win_IRE=0|draw_IRE=0|loss_IRE=3|gf_IRE=2|ga_IRE=12\n\n|col_C=#ccffcc|text_C=\n|result1=C\n|update=complete|source=<ref name=\"EUF\">{{cite web |title=British Championship 1909 |url=https://eu-football.info/_tournament.php?id=BC-26 |website=EU-Football.Info |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n|class_rules = 1) points. The points system worked as follows: 2 points for a win and 1 point for a draw.\n}}</onlyinclude>\n\n==Results==\n{{football box \n | date = 13 February 1909\n | team1 = {{fb-rt|ENG}}\n | score = 4 \u2013 0\n | team2 = {{fb|IRE}}\n | goals1 = {{goal|60||80|}} [[Vivian Woodward]]<br />{{goal|50||87|pen.|}} [[George Hilsdon]]  \n | goals2 = &nbsp; \n | stadium = [[Park Avenue (stadium)|Park Avenue]], [[Bradford]]\n | attendance = 28,000\n | referee = James Stark ([[Scottish Football Association|Scotland]])\n}}\n----\n{{football box \n | date = 1 March 1909\n | team1 = {{fb-rt|WAL|1807}}\n | score = 3  \u2013 2\n | team2 = {{fb|SCO}}\n | goals1 = [[William Davies (footballer born 1882)|William Davies]] {{goal|23||39}}<br />[[Lot Jones]] {{goal|26}}\n | goals2 = {{goal|70}} [[Bobby Walker (footballer born 1879)|Bobby Walker]]<br />{{goal|73}} [[Harold Paul]]\n | stadium = [[Racecourse Ground]], [[Wrexham]] \n | attendance = 6,000\n | referee = Thomas P. Campbell ([[The Football Association|England]])\n}}\n----\n{{f