ness\n|isbn = 0-85112-954-4 }}\n\n{{British Home Championship}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Home Championship}}\n[[Category:1909 in British sport]]\n[[Category:1908\u201309 in Irish association football|Brit]]\n[[Category:1908\u201309 in Welsh football|Brit]]\n[[Category:1908\u201309 in English football]]\n[[Category:1908\u201309 in Scottish football]]\n[[Category:British Home Championships|1908-09]]\n", "name_user": "Muchclag", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected date in infobox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1908%E2%80%9309_British_Home_Championship"}
{"title_page": "Richard Lalor", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=January 2017}}\n'''Richard Lalor''' (1823 \u2013 13 November 1893) was [[Irish people|Irish]] [[Nationalist]] Member of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] for [[Queen's County (UK Parliament constituency)|Queen's County]], 1880\u201385 and for [[Queen's County Leix (UK Parliament constituency)|Queen's County (Leix)]], 1885\u201392.\n\nHe was the son of [[Patrick \"Patt\" Lalor]] of Tenakill, Mountrath, Queen's County, who had himself been an M.P. for Queen's County in 1832\u201335.  His eldest brother was [[James Fintan Lalor]] and his younger brother was the Australian politician [[Peter Lalor]].  His mother was Anna, daughter of Patrick Dillon of Sheane.  He was educated privately and became a civil engineer and tenant farmer.  Like his brother James Fintan, he was a [[Young Ireland]]er.  In 1852 he married Margaret, daughter of Michael Dunne of Mountrath.  He became a magistrate for Queen's County.\n\nHe headed the poll as a Parnellite Home Ruler in the election for the two Queen's County seats in 1880, ousting the former Home Rule member, Kenelm Digby.  He then won the new Queen's County (Leix) seat in 1885, defeating his Conservative opponent by more than 7 to 1.  He won again in 1886, by an even bigger margin.\n\n[[T. P. O'Connor]] described him in 1886:  \u2018Today he is a feeble and bent man with wearied eyes and a thin voice, but his spirit is exactly the same as in his hot youth.  In 1848 he had his pike and his thousands of pikemen ready for action;  today, as then, he is the unconquerable and irreclaimable rebel \u2013 the [[Louis Auguste Blanqui|Blanqui]] of Irish politics.\u2019<ref>O'Connor, The Parnell Movement, London, 1886, p.367</ref>\n\nWhen the Irish Parliamentary Party split in December 1890 over the leadership of [[Charles Stewart Parnell]], Lalor supported Parnell.  However failing health prevented him from campaigning in the general election of 1892, and he was ousted from his seat.<ref>''Irish Times'', 14 November 1893</ref>\n\nHe died at his home at Tenakill, Queen's County, on Monday 13 November 1893. His grandson [[John Lalor Fitzpatrick]] (1875\u20131956) was also a nationalist member of the House of Commons for the Ossory division of Queen's County (1916\u201318).<ref>Patrick F. Meehan \"The members of Parliament for Lais and Offaly 1801-1918\" Leinster Express Press 1972 Portaloise p. 78</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite news|title=Irish Times|date=14 November 1893|publisher=Irish Times}}\n*{{cite book|last=O'Connor|first=T.P|title=The Parnell Movement|url=https://archive.org/details/parnellmovement01ocon|location=London|year=1886}}\n*{{cite news|title=The Times|date=27 November 1885|publisher=The Times}}\n*{{cite book|title=Parliamentary Election Results in Ireland, 1801-1922|editor=Brian M. Walker|publisher=Royal Irish Academy|location=Dublin|year=1978}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{hansard-contribs | mr-richard-lalor | Richard Lalor }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Kenelm Thomas Digby]] <br />[[Edmund Dease]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Queen's County (UK Parliament constituency)|Queen's County]]\n       |with   = [[Arthur O'Connor (MP)|Arthur O'Connor]]\n       |years  = [[1880 United Kingdom general election|1880]] \u2013 [[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885]]}}\n{{s-non|reason = Constituency divided}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Queen's County Leix (UK Parliament constituency)|Queen's County Leix]] |years  = [[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885]] \u2013 [[1892 United Kingdom general election|1892]]}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Mark MacDonnell]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lalor, Richard}}\n[[Category:1823 births]]\n[[Category:1893 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Carlow College]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Queen's County constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1880\u20131885]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1885\u20131886]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1886\u20131892]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=January 2017}}\n'''Richard Lalor''' (1823 \u2013 13 November 1893) was [[Irish people|Irish]] [[Nationalist]] Member of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] for [[Queen's County (UK Parliament constituency)|Queen's County]], 1880\u201385 and for [[Queen's County Leix (UK Parliament constituency)|Queen's County (Leix)]], 1885\u201392.\n\nHe was the son of [[Patrick \"Patt\" Lalor]] of Tenakill, Mountrath, Queen\u2019s County, who had himself been an M.P. for Queen\u2019s County in 1832-35.  His eldest brother was [[James Fintan Lalor]] and his younger brother was the Australian politician [[Peter Lalor]].  His mother was Anna, daughter of Patrick Dillon of Sheane.  He was educated privately and became a civil engineer and tenant farmer.  Like his brother James Fintan, he was a [[Young Ireland]]er.  In 1852 he married Margaret, daughter of Michael Dunne of Mountrath.  He became a magistrate for Queen\u2019s County.\n\nHe headed the poll as a Parnellite Home Ruler in the election for the two Queen\u2019s County seats in 1880, ousting the former Home Rule member, Kenelm Digby.  He then won the new Queen\u2019s County (Leix) seat in 1885, defeating his Conservative opponent by more than 7 to 1.  He won again in 1886, by an even bigger margin.\n\n[[T. P. O'Connor]] described him in 1886:  \u2018Today he is a feeble and bent man with wearied eyes and a thin voice, but his spirit is exactly the same as in his hot youth.  In 1848 he had his pike and his thousands of pikemen ready for action;  today, as then, he is the unconquerable and irreclaimable rebel \u2013 the [[Louis Auguste Blanqui|Blanqui]] of Irish politics.\u2019<ref>O'Connor, The Parnell Movement, London, 1886, p.367</ref>\n\nWhen the Irish Parliamentary Party split in December 1890 over the leadership of [[Charles Stewart Parnell]], Lalor supported Parnell.  However failing health prevented him from campaigning in the general election of 1892, and he was ousted from his seat.<ref>''Irish Times'', 14 November 1893</ref>\n\nHe died at his home at Tenakill, Queen\u2019s County, on Monday 13 November 1893. His grandson [[John Lalor Fitzpatrick]] (1875\u20131956) was also a nationalist member of the House of Commons for the Ossory division of Queen's County (1916\u201318).<ref>Patrick F. Meehan \"The members of Parliament for Lais and Offaly 1801-1918\" Leinster Express Press 1972 Portaloise p. 78</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite news|title=Irish Times|date=14 November 1893|publisher=Irish Times}}\n*{{cite book|last=O'Connor|first=T.P|title=The Parnell Movement|url=https://archive.org/details/parnellmovement01ocon|location=London|year=1886}}\n*{{cite news|title=The Times|date=27 November 1885|publisher=The Times}}\n*{{cite book|title=Parliamentary Election Results in Ireland, 1801-1922|editor=Brian M. Walker|publisher=Royal Irish Academy|location=Dublin|year=1978}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{hansard-contribs | mr-richard-lalor | Richard Lalor }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Kenelm Thomas Digby]] <br />[[Edmund Dease]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Queen's County (UK Parliament constituency)|Queen's County]]\n       |with   = [[Arthur O'Connor (MP)|Arthur O'Connor]]\n       |years  = [[1880 United Kingdom general election|1880]] \u2013 [[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885]]}}\n{{s-non|reason = Constituency divided}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Queen's County Leix (UK Parliament constituency)|Queen's County Leix]] |years  = [[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885]] \u2013 [[1892 United Kingdom general election|1892]]}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Mark MacDonnell]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lalor, Richard}}\n[[Category:1823 births]]\n[[Category:1893 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Carlow College]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Queen's County constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1880\u20131885]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1885\u20131886]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1886\u20131892]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (6), 1832-35 \u2192 1832\u201335", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Lalor"}
{"title_page": "Hubert Jerningham", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix   = \n|name               = Hubert Jerningham\n|native_name        = \n|native_name_lang   = \n|honorific-suffix   = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|KCMG|DL}}\n|image              = \n|caption            = \n|office1             = [[Governor of British Mauritius|Governor]] of [[Mauritius]]\n|term_start1         = 1892\n|term_end1           = 1897\n|monarch1            = [[Queen Victoria|Victoria]]\n|governor-general1   = \n|predecessor1        = Sur [[Charles Lees (colonial administrator)|Charles Lees]]\n|successor1          = Sir [[Charles Bruce (governor)|Charles Bruce]]\n|office             = [[List of Governors of Trinidad and Tobago|Governor]] of [[Trinidad and Tobago]]\n|term_start         = 1897\n|term_end           = 1900\n|monarch            = [[Queen Victoria|Victoria]]\n|governor-general   = \n|predecessor        = Sir [[Frederick Broome]]\n|successor          = Sir [[Cornelius Alfred Moloney]]\n|birth_date         = {{birth date|df=y|1842|10|18}}\n|birth_place        = \n|death_date         = {{death date and age|df=y|1914|4|3|1842|10|18}}\n|death_place        = \n}}\n\n'''Sir Hubert Edward Henry Jerningham''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|sep=,|KCMG|DL}} (18 October 1842<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=wN8NAAAAQAAJ&q=Sir+Hubert+Edward+Henry+Jerningham+1842&dq=Sir+Hubert+Edward+Henry+Jerningham+1842&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj34bOP3vXWAhWDCBoKHfcQAIQQ6AEIUDAJ]</ref> \u2013 3 April 1914)<ref>https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=125635355</ref> was [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] politician and Governor of [[Mauritius]] 1892\u20131897, then Governor of [[Trinidad and Tobago]] between 1897 and 1900.\n\n==Biography==\nJerningham was [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Berwick-upon-Tweed (UK Parliament constituency)|Berwick-upon-Tweed]] from 1881 to 1885.\n\nHe was appointed the 17th [[Governor of British Mauritius|Governor of Mauritius]], from 21 September 1892 to 15 January 1897, having been previously acting in the role from 12 March 1892 to 20 September 1892.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldstatesmen.org/Mauritius.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-03-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5hOqWZAh1?url=http://www.worldstatesmen.org/Mauritius.htm |archivedate=9 June 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn June 1897 he was appointed [[Governor of Trinidad and Tobago]], serving as such until December 1900. While he was Governor, the [[Trinidad Government Railway]] was extended from [[Cunupia]] to [[Tabaquite]]. The railway junction formed by this extension was named [[Jerningham Junction]].  He also instituted an award for the top student in the [[Island Scholarship]] examinations, a gold medal called the ''Jerningham Medal'' (today known as the ''President's Medal''). Jerningham advised the [[Colonial Office]] to suspend the charter of the Borough of [[Port of Spain]] in 1898 following a dispute with the Borough Council. The borough charter was suspended on 1 January 1899; the suspension remained in effect until 1914. This action made Jerningham very unpopular with the population.\n\nJerningham was appointed a [[deputy lieutenant]] of [[Northumberland]] on 21 May 1901, after his return to the [[United Kingdom]].<ref name=\"may901\">{{London Gazette | issue=27317 |page=3562 | date=24 May 1901}}</ref> He was received in a customary stepping down audience by [[Edward VII|King Edward VII]] in January 1902.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Court circular |day_of_week=Friday |date=31 January 1902 |page_number=8 |issue=36679| }}</ref> He settled at [[Longridge Towers School|Longridge Towers]], where he had erected a stately home, said to among the largest private houses in that part of the country.\n\n==Family==\nJerningham married in 1874 Annie Liddell, daughter of Edward Liddell, of Benton park, [[Northumberland]]. She was the widow of Charles Mather, and had inherited the Longridge Towers estate near [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]] and other property from her first husband. Lady Jerningham died at Longridge Towers on 9 October 1902.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Obituary - Lady Jerningham |day_of_week=Friday |date=10 October 1902 |page_number=9 |issue=36895| }}</ref>\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book | author=[[Michael Anthony (author)|Anthony, Michael]] | title=Historical Dictionary of Trinidad and Tobago | publisher=Scarecrow Press, Inc.  Lanham, Md., and London | year=2001 |isbn=0-8108-3173-2}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20181015041700/http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Bcommons2.htm Historical list of MPs: B, part 2]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Gutenberg author | id=Jerningham,+Hubert+E.+H.+(Hubert+Edward+Henry),+Sir}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Hubert Jerningham}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Berwick-upon-Tweed (UK Parliament constituency)|Berwick-upon-Tweed]]\n  | with   = [[David Milne Home (politician)|David Milne Home]]\n  | years  = 1881\u2013[[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885]]\n  | before = [[David Milne Home (politician)|David Milne Home]]  | before2=[[Dudley Marjoribanks, 1st Baron Tweedmouth|Dudley Marjoribanks]]\n  | after  = [[Edward Grey, 1st Viscount Grey of Fallodon|Sir Edward Grey]]\n}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Governor of British Mauritius|Governor of Mauritius]]\n  | years  = 1892\u20131897\n  | before = [[Charles Lees (colonial administrator)|Sir Charles Cameron Lees]]\n  | after  = [[Charles Bruce (governor)|Sir Charles Bruce]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[List of Governors of Trinidad and Tobago|Governor of Trinidad and Tobago]]\n  | years  = 1897\u20131900\n  | before = [[Frederick Broome|Frederick Napier Broome]]\n  | after  = [[Cornelius Alfred Moloney]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jerningham, Hubert}}\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Northumberland]]\n[[Category:Governors of Trinidad and Tobago]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1880\u20131885]]\n[[Category:1842 births]]\n[[Category:1914 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix   = \n|name               = Hubert Jerningham\n|native_name        = \n|native_name_lang   = \n|honorific-suffix   = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|KCMG|DL}}\n|image              = \n|caption            = \n|office1             = [[Governor of British Mauritius|Governor]] of [[Mauritius]]\n|term_start1         = 1892\n|term_end1           = 1897\n|monarch1            = [[Queen Victoria|Victoria]]\n|governor-general1   = \n|predecessor1        = Sur [[Charles Lees (colonial administrator)|Charles Lees]]\n|successor1          = Sir [[Charles Bruce (governor)|Charles Bruce]]\n|office             = [[List of Governors of Trinidad and Tobago|Governor]] of [[Trinidad and Tobago]]\n|term_start         = 1897\n|term_end           = 1900\n|monarch            = [[Queen Victoria|Victoria]]\n|governor-general   = \n|predecessor        = Sir [[Frederick Broome]]\n|successor          = Sir [[Cornelius Alfred Moloney]]\n|birth_date         = {{birth date|df=y|1842|10|18}}\n|birth_place        = \n|death_date         = {{death date and age|df=y|1914|4|3|1842|10|18}}\n|death_place        = \n}}\n\n'''Sir Hubert Edward Henry Jerningham''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|sep=,|KCMG|DL}} (18 October 1842<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=wN8NAAAAQAAJ&q=Sir+Hubert+Edward+Henry+Jerningham+1842&dq=Sir+Hubert+Edward+Henry+Jerningham+1842&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj34bOP3vXWAhWDCBoKHfcQAIQQ6AEIUDAJ]</ref> \u2013 3 April 1914)<ref>https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page