Examiner]]''<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfexaminer.com/entertainment/2019-the-best-in-film/|title=2019: The best in film|date=31 December 2019|website=The San Francisco Examiner|access-date=1 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101142411/https://www.sfexaminer.com/entertainment/2019-the-best-in-film/|archive-date=1 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 8th{{snd}} Anita Katz, ''[[San Francisco Examiner]]''<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* 8th{{snd}} [[Col Needham]], ''[[IMDb]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/best-of/col-needham-best-movies-of-2019/ls091254728/?ref_=pe_3465290_461832910_eml_eh_hero_eml_stat_hero |title=Col Needham's Best Movies of 2019 |last=Needham |first=Col |access-date=22 December 2019}}</ref>\n* 9th{{snd}} Richard Whittaker, ''[[The Austin Chronicle]]''<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/screens/2019-12-20/richard-whittakers-top-10-films-of-2019/ |title=Richard Whittaker's Top 10 Films of 2019 |last=Whittaker |first=Richard |date=20 December 2019 |newspaper=[[Austin Chronicle]] |access-date=22 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191220152603/https://www.austinchronicle.com/screens/2019-12-20/richard-whittakers-top-10-films-of-2019/ |archive-date=20 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 9th{{snd}} Dann Gire, ''[[Chicago Daily Herald]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyherald.com/entlife/20191228/parasite-little-women-and-marriage-story-lead-list-of-2019s-best-films|title='Parasite,' 'Little Women' and 'Marriage Story' lead list of 2019's best films|first=Dann|last=Gire|date=28 December 2019|website=Daily Herald|access-date=3 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103005825/https://www.dailyherald.com/entlife/20191228/parasite-little-women-and-marriage-story-lead-list-of-2019s-best-films|archive-date=3 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 9th{{snd}} Mike Scott, ''[[New Orleans Times-Picayune]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nola.com/entertainment_life/festivals/article_b4a74128-2515-11ea-8ff4-37c07347ad9a.html|title=The best movies of 2019: Movie critic Mike Scott unveils his favorite films of the year|first=MIKE SCOTT &#124; Contributing|last=writer|website=NOLA.com|access-date=1 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101142023/https://www.nola.com/entertainment_life/festivals/article_b4a74128-2515-11ea-8ff4-37c07347ad9a.html|archive-date=1 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 10th{{snd}} Max Weiss, ''[[Baltimore Magazine]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baltimoremagazine.com/section/artsentertainment/my-favorite-films-of-2019|title=My Favorite Films of 2019|first=Baltimore|last=magazine|date=13 December 2019|website=Baltimore magazine|access-date=15 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214162114/https://www.baltimoremagazine.com/section/artsentertainment/my-favorite-films-of-2019|archive-date=14 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n=== Accolades ===\n{{Main|List of accolades received by 1917 (2019 film)}}\n''1917'' received ten nominations at the [[92nd Academy Awards]], winning for [[Visual Effects]], [[Academy Award for Best Sound Mixing|Sound Mixing]], and [[Cinematography]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/movies/story/2020-01-13/oscar-nominations-2020-joker-irishman-1917-netflix|title='Joker' tops this year's Oscar nominations, with '1917,' 'Irishman,' 'Once Upon a Time' close behind|date=13 January 2020|website=Los Angeles Times|first=Josh|last=Rottenberg|language=en-US|access-date=13 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113155142/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/movies/story/2020-01-13/oscar-nominations-2020-joker-irishman-1917-netflix|archive-date=13 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It received three nominations at the [[77th Golden Globe Awards]] and won two awards: for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Drama|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Drama]] and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Director|Best Director]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/google-amp/news/golden-globes-2020-the-full-winners-list-joker-chernobyl-joaquin-phoenix/|title=Golden Globes 2020: The full winners list|last=Bisset|first=Jennifer|website=[[CNET]]|date=5 January 2020|accessdate=9 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106070941/https://www.cnet.com/google-amp/news/golden-globes-2020-the-full-winners-list-joker-chernobyl-joaquin-phoenix/|archive-date=6 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\nIt also received eight nominations at the [[25th Critics' Choice Awards]], winning three awards, including Best Director,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/awards/critics-choice-the-irishman-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-lead-movie-nominations-1203428878/|title=Critics' Choice: 'The Irishman,' 'Once Upon a Time in Hollywood' Lead Movie Nominations|work=Variety|first1=Marc|last1=Malkin|date=8 December 2019|access-date=8 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191209013912/https://variety.com/2019/film/awards/critics-choice-the-irishman-once-upon-a-time-in-hollywood-lead-movie-nominations-1203428878/|archive-date=9 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and nine nominations at the [[73rd British Academy Film Awards]], winning the most awards \u2014 seven, including [[BAFTA Award for Best Film|Best Film]], [[BAFTA Award for Best Direction|Best Director]] and [[BAFTA Award for Best British Film|Outstanding British film]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/bafta-awards-2020-nominations-unveiled-1267114|title=BAFTA Nominations: 'Joker' Leads the Pack|last=Ritman|first=Alex|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=6 January 2020|accessdate=7 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107092213/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/bafta-awards-2020-nominations-unveiled-1267114|archive-date=7 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/feb/02/baftas-2020-sam-mendes-and-1917-emerge-victorious-with-seven-awards|title=Baftas 2020: Sam Mendes and 1917 emerge victorious with seven awards|last=Brown|first=Mark |website=[[The Guardian]]|date=2 February 2020|accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref>. Finally, it won the Most Valuable Film of 2020's award by [[Cinema for Peace]]. It was chosen by the [[National Board of Review]] and the [[American Film Institute]] as one of the top ten films of the year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/irishman-tops-national-board-review-2019-honorees-full-list-1259206|title='The Irishman' Named Best Film by National Board of Review|date=3 December 2019|first=Hilary|last=Lewis|website=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=4 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191205014534/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/irishman-tops-national-board-review-2019-honorees-full-list-1259206|archive-date=5 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afi.com/news/afi-awards-2019-honorees-announced/|title=AFI AWARDS 2019 Honorees Announced|website=American Film Institute|language=en|access-date=4 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191210160159/https://www.afi.com/news/afi-awards-2019-honorees-announced/|archive-date=10 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Historical accuracy ==\n[[File:Sherwood Foresters following up Germans near Brie March 1917 IWM Q 1863.jpg|thumb|British soldiers following up the Germans near [[Brie, Somme|Brie]], March 1917]]\nThe film was inspired by [[Operation Alberich]], a German withdrawal to new positions on the shorter and more easily defended [[Hindenburg Line]] that took place between 9 February and 20 March 1917.<ref>{{cite news |title=Operation Alberich, the campaign that inspired Sam Mendes' 1917 |url=https://www.history.co.uk/article/operation-alberich-the-campaign-that-inspired-sam-mendes-1917 |work=History.co.uk}}</ref> However, the main and supporting characters all appear to be fictional.<ref>{{cite news |title=1917 was Inspired by a True Story Sam Mendes' Grandfather Told to Him |url=http://www.historyvshollywood.com/reelfaces/1917/ |work=History vs. Hollywood}}</ref>\n\nWriting in the ''[[New York Times]]'', Cathy Tempelsman argues that the storyline offers a \"dangerously misleading\" picture of the War, suggesting \"a concern for the sanctity of human life from the top down\", whereas the reality was \"an appalling indifference as the British high command sent hundreds of thousands of their young men to die\".  She adds that the \"false heroics and filmmaking feats of wonder\" serve to provide an \"escape from the true carnage of the 'Great War'\", and that in reality the scale of the [[World War I casualties|casualties]] was such that the potential loss of 1,600 men would not have excited the response portrayed in the film.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/08/opinion/1917-movie-world-war-I.html|newspaper=New York Times|date=8 February 2020|first=Cathy|last=Tempelsman|accessdate=11 February 2020|title='1917' Turns a Horrific War Into an Uplifting Hero's Journey}}</ref>\n\nAccording to military historian Jeremy Banning, \"It made no sense, as the film depicts, to have some battalions nine miles beyond the former German line and others seemingly unaware of whether this line was manned. ... As for the assault by the Devons, no unit would attack without adequate artillery support\".<ref>{{cite news |title=\"A staggering tour de force \u2013 but an opportunity missed\": a historian's review of the film 1917 |url=https://www.historyextra.com/period/first-world-war/1917-film-historian-review-real-history-ww1-what-happened-how-plausible-accurate/ |work=HistoryExtra |date=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe film has a multiracial supporting cast, with black and Indian actors portraying British soldiers in the trenches. In reality, the number of black soldiers serving in the [[British Army during World War I|British Army]] (rather than [[Colonial troops|colonial regiments]]) during World War I is unknown but is likely to have been negligible. The [[Devonshire Regiment]] was never brigaded with any West Indian or African units (it spent the war in [[8th Infantry Division (United Kingdom)|8th Division]]). Over 15,000 men from the Caribbean enlisted, including black Caribbeans living in Britain, and by 1915 it was decided to group them together into a single regiment, named the [[British West Indies Regiment]].<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite news |title=Fact-checking 1917: how historically accurate is Sam Mendes's First World War film? |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/0/1917-fact-checking-how-historically-accurate-sam-mendes-war-movie/ |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=10 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=-6RACwAAQBAJ&pg=PA97 |title=Colonial Soldiers in Europe, 1914\u20131945: \"Aliens in Uniform\" in Wartime Societies |pages=97\u2013102|date=22 December 2015|website=|isbn=9781317330981|last1=Storm |first1=Eric |last2=Tuma |first2=Ali Al }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=How accurate is Sam Mendes's film, 1917? |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/how-accurate-is-sam-mendess-film-1917-8mtbrbfkv |work=The Times |date=6 January 2020}}</ref> Indian [[Sikhs]] would have served in their own regiments as part of the [[British Indian Army]], not as individuals in the ranks of British regiments and Corps. By 1917 the Indian infantry had been withdrawn from the Western Front and sent to the Middle East; the Indian cavalry remained.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=India and the Western Front |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/worldwars/wwone/india_wwone_01.shtml |publisher=BBC \u2013 History}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|United Kingdom|Film|World War I}}\n* [[Real time (media)|Real time]]\n* ''[[Dunkirk (2017 film)|Dunkirk]]''\n* ''[[All Quiet on the Western Front]]''\n* [[List of World War I films]]\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n* {{AllMovie title}}\n\n{{1917 (2019 film)}}\n{{Sam Mendes}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of accolades received by 1917 (2019 film)|Awards for ''1917'']]\n|list =\n{{BAFTA Best Film}}\n{{BAFTA Best British Film}}\n{{Golden Globe Award Best Motion Picture Drama}}\n{{Producers Guild of America Award for Best Theatrical Motion Picture}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:2010s action drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s historical films]]\n[[Category:2010s war drama films]]\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:Amblin Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:American action drama films]]\n[[Category:American epic films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American historical films]]\n[[Category:American war drama films]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (films)]]\n[[Category:Best Drama Picture Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:British action drama films]]\n[[Category:British epic films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British historical films]]\n[[Category:British war drama films]]\n[[Category:DreamWorks Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Entertainment One films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Sam Mendes]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Thomas Newman]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1917]]\n[[Category:Films shot at Shepperton Studios]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Surrey]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:Films set in France]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Best Sound Mixing Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Best Visual Effects Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Films whose cinematographer won the Best Cinematography Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Reliance Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Western Front (World War I) films]]\n", "name_user": "Doron.t.rose", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePlot:fixed confusing syntax about rings and dog tags passing between Blake brothers, while maintaining custom of Tom Blake referred to as \"Blake\" and Joseph Blake referred to as \"Joseph\")", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1917_(2019_film)"}
{"title_page": "John Whittaker Ellis", "text_new": "{{More footnotes|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name = Sir John Whittaker Ellis\n|honorific-suffix = [[Baronet|Bt]] [[Justice of the Peace|JP]]\n|image = John Whitaker Ellis Vanity Fair 4 November 1882.jpg\n|caption = Caricature by [[Leslie Ward|Spy]] published in [[Vanity Fair (British magazine 1868-1914)|Vanity Fair]] in 1882.\n|office1 = [[Lord Mayor of the City of London]]\n|term_start1 = 1881\n|term_end1 = 1882\n|predecessor1 = [[William McArthur (Lord Mayor of London)|William McArthur]]\n|successor1 = Henry Knight\n|birth_date = 25 January 1829<ref name=who>\"Ellis, Sir (John) Whittaker, (25 Jan. 1829\u201320 Sept. 1912).\" WHO'S WHO & WHO WAS WHO.  December 01, 2007. Oxford University Press. Date of access 3 Dec. 2019, <https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540891.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-185738></ref>\n|death_date = 20 September 1912 (aged 83)<ref name=who/>\n| nationality = [[British people|British]]\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|alma_mater = Rev. William Allan's School<ref name=who/>\n|spouse = (1) Mary Ann Staples (d. 1901)<br>(2) Marian Bailey<ref name=who/>\n}}\n{{other people|John Ellis}}\n\n[[File:St Peter's Church, Petersham 05.JPG|thumb|Pyramidal [[stone slab]] on massive stone base above his family grave by [[St Peter's Church, Petersham]]]]\n'''Sir John Whittaker Ellis, 1st Baronet''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|JP}}<ref name=who/> (1829-1912) was [[Lord Mayor of London]] for 1881\u20131882 in which year he was made a baronet.  Two years later he was elected and re-elected [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for eight years, not seeking further re-election.  A very prosperous banking executive, estate agent and auctioneer among his legacies was a fire station at [[Byfleet]], [[Surrey]]; he sat on the boards of various hospitals and his wife was also engaged in charities.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in 1829, Ellis was the fifth son of Joseph Ellis, owner of the [[Star and Garter Hotel, Richmond|Star and Garter Hotel]] in Petersham, [[Richmond, London|Richmond]], Surrey (now London) from 1830\u20131847.\n\nHe set up his family in [[Byfleet]], living for many years at Petersham House/Place (built in High Road {{abbreviation|c.|circa (about)}} 1859, its surviving front block is 15 High Road, used as [[Lloyds Bank]] and a risk consultancy).  After a fire there, Ellis organised Byfleet's first fire brigade. He equipped three of his market/domestic gardeners &ndash; the Place had attached 17 acres<ref>https://maps.nls.uk/geo/explore/#zoom=18&lat=51.3398&lon=-0.4778&layers=168&b=1</ref> &ndash; with three lengths of hose and an obsolete manual pump, put on wheels, kept in a potting shed. \n\nHe was a banking executive, auctioneer and estate agent, as well as holding local government posts including alderman of Broad Street Ward, 1872\u20131909, [[Sheriff of London]] and Middlesex, 1874\u201375, [[Lord Mayor of London]], 1881\u201382, and mayor of Richmond, 1890\u201391.<ref name=aim>{{cite web | url = http://www.aim25.ac.uk/cgi-bin/vcdf/detail?coll_id=19166&inst_id=118&nv1=search&nv2=| title = ELLIS, Sir John Whittaker (1829-1912)|publisher= AIM25|accessdate = 2012-08-10}}</ref> He was also a magistrate (Justice of the Peace); Governor of the Irish Society, 1882\u201394, governor of various hospitals and High Sheriff of Surrey, 1899\u20131900.<ref name=aim/>\n\nHe was elected for one of the two [[Member of Parliament|seats]] for [[Mid Surrey (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Surrey]] at a [[by-election]] in 1884. When that area was abolished he was nominated for and won the [[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885 general election]] and that of the next year for the inceptive [[Kingston-upon-Thames (UK Parliament constituency)|Kingston upon Thames]] seat which took in Richmond but retired in 1892. Hansard records 20 contributions of his, making some each year to 1891 inclusive.<ref>{{hansard-contribs | sir-john-ellis | Sir John Ellis, Bt }}</ref>\n\nOn 6 June 1882 he was made a [[baronet]], of Byfleet in the County of Surrey, and of Hertford Street, Mayfair, in the County of Middlesex,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=25114 |date=2 June 1882 |page=2589 }}</ref> a title which became extinct on his death. He later became the [[Municipal Borough of Richmond (Surrey)|Borough of Richmond]]'s first Mayor, and purchased the site for Richmond's [[Old Town Hall, Richmond|first town hall]].<ref name=\"Old Town Hall\">{{cite web | url=http://www.richmond.gov.uk/home/leisure_and_culture/local_history_and_heritage/local_studies_collection/local_history_timelines/old_town_hall_timeline.htm | title=Old Town Hall timeline | publisher=[[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]] | work=Local History Timelines | accessdate=18 December 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819091340/http://www.richmond.gov.uk/home/leisure_and_culture/local_history_and_heritage/local_studies_collection/local_history_timelines/old_town_hall_timeline.htm | archive-date=19 August 2016 | url-status=dead }}</ref>  In 1899 he was appointed [[High Sheriff of Surrey]] for the year.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27061|page=1660|date=10 March 1899}}</ref> He remarried in 1903, to Marian Bailey.\n\nHe was appointed Director of Alliance Bank, 1880, then its Chairman, 1883\u201386; and served years as Chairman of Emanuel Hospital to 1909.<ref name=who/>\n\nEllis died without offspring on 20 September 1912 and is buried in [[Petersham Parish Church|St Peter's churchyard, Petersham]].<ref name=\"Local History Notes Petersham\">{{cite web | url=http://www.richmond.gov.uk/local_history_st_peters_petersham.pdf | title=St Peter's Church, Petersham | publisher=[[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]] | work=Local History Notes | accessdate=18 December 2012 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426233438/http://www.richmond.gov.uk/local_history_st_peters_petersham.pdf | archivedate=26 April 2012 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Legacies==\n[[File:Houses_at_Wormleybury_-_geograph.org.uk_-_472899.jpg|thumb|The summary of his probate's extraction states he lived at (the house known as) [[Wormleybury]], Hertfordshire]]\nIn 1885, he funded Byfleet Fire Station which would house a volunteer fire brigade. Initially the [[Civil parishes in England|(civil) Parish]] managed this, renting its building and an engine from Ellis.  The building was used until 1963, latterly as part of the Surrey Fire Brigade. The building is little changed and became a Grade II [[Listed building]] in 2008.<ref>{{NHLE|num=1392421|desc=The Old Fire Station, 40 High Road}}</ref>  15 High Road, his former front block of the family home, is locally listed, under category \"AH\", architectural merit.<ref>[https://www.woking.gov.uk/sites/default/files/documents/planning-and-building-control/herritage/planningheritage.pdf Local Listed Building no. 191], ''The Heritage of Woking'', amended 2000, Borough of Woking: Planning Service, p 12 of 100.</ref>\n\nIn 1895 a bust of Ellis was unveiled in the town hall by [[Princess Mary Adelaide of Cambridge|Mary Adelaide, Duchess of Teck]]<ref name=\"Old Town Hall\"/>  this is still displayed in the staircase alcove.<ref>[http://www.richmond.gov.uk/home/leisure_and_culture/local_history_and_heritage/local_studies_collection/local_history_timelines/old_town_hall_timeline/bust_of_sir_john_wittaker_ellis.htm Photograph and details of bust of Ellis in the Old Town Hall] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120902035640/http://www.richmond.gov.uk/home/leisure_and_culture/local_history_and_heritage/local_studies_collection/local_history_timelines/old_town_hall_timeline/bust_of_sir_john_wittaker_ellis.htm |date=2 September 2012 }} London Borough of Richmond-on-Thames: Local History and Heritage: Old Town Hall Timeline</ref>\n\nHis wife shares a large stone monument above their grave, in the related church he has a plaque in north chancel.<ref name=\"Local History Notes Petersham\"/>\n\nHe is further commemorated by Whittaker Avenue, Richmond.<ref name=\"Local History Notes Petersham\"/>  His probate was resworn in 1912 leaving assets of {{GBP|181969|1912|round=-5|about=yes|long=no}} <ref>https://probatesearch.service.gov.uk Calendar of Probates and Administrations</ref>\n\n==Lady Ellis==\nJohn Whittaker Ellis married, in 1859, Mary Anne Staples, daughter of John Staples.\n\nThe first Lady Ellis was a prominent Mayoress both in London and in Richmond, and was identified with many charities in the then greater forms of [[Surrey]] (reduced to reflect expansion of [[London]] itself in her lifetime and further in 1965). She was president of the Ladies\u00b4 Committee of the Royal Cambridge Asylum for 70 military widows ([[East Molesey]]), and on the death of [[Princess Mary Adelaide of Cambridge|Princess Mary Adelaide, Duchess of Teck]] in 1897 was appointed to succeed her as county president of the Surrey Needlework Guild. She was also one of the presidents of the [[Soldiers' and Sailors' Families Association]] and took a prominent part in the establishment of the [[National Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children|Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children]]. She died at Buccleuch House, [[Richmond, London|Richmond, Surrey]], on 18 December 1901.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Obituaries - Lady Ellis |day_of_week=Thursday |date=19 December 1901 |page_number=6 |issue=36642}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nHe circulated pamphlets entitled or concerning: \"The Land Question, Government of Ireland etc.\"<ref name=who/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Old Town Hall, Richmond]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Byfleet Heritage Society archives\n* Stevens, Leonard R (2001, 2nd edition reprint by the Byfleet Heritage Society) \u2018Byfleet \u2013 A Village of England\u2019 (The Byfleet Heritage Society, Byfleet, Surrey).\n* Wakeford, Iain (1983) \u2018Bygone Woking\u2019 (Phillimore & Co Ltd, Chichester, {{ISBN|0-85033-506-X}}).\n* Wakeford, Iain (2000) \u2018Byfleet \u2013 A Heritage Walks Guide\u2019 (AK, HR & DA Wakeford, Old Woking, Surrey)\n*{{Rayment-bt|date=March 2012}}\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n*[http://www.byfleetheritage.org.uk/ Byfleet Heritage Society website]\n\n== External links ==\n* {{hansard-contribs | sir-john-ellis | Sir John Ellis, Bt }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-civ}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Lord Mayor of the City of London]] | before=[[William McArthur (Lord Mayor of London)|William McArthur]] | after=[[Henry Knight (Lord Mayor of London)|Henry Knight]] | years=1881\u20131882}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Sir Henry Peek, 1st Baronet|Sir Henry Peek, Bt]]\n | before2 = [[Sir Trevor Lawrence, 2nd Baronet|Sir Trevor Lawrence, Bt]]\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Mid Surrey (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Surrey]]\n | years = [[1884 Mid Surrey by-election|1884]] \u2013 [[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885]]\n | with  = [[Sir Trevor Lawrence, 2nd Baronet|Sir Trevor Lawrence, Bt]]\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = Constituency abolished }}\n{{s-new | constituency }}\n{{s-ttl\n  | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Kingston-upon-Thames (UK Parliament constituency)|Kingston]]\n  | years = [[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885]] \u2013 [[1892 United Kingdom general election|1892]]\n}}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[Sir Richard Temple, 1st Baronet|Sir Richard Temple, Bt]] }}\n{{s-reg|uk-bt}}\n{{s-new | creation }}\n{{s-ttl\n  | title  = [[Ellis baronets|Baronet]]<br />'''(of Byfleet and Hertford Street)'''\n  | years  = 1882 \u2013 1912\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = Extinct }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ellis, John}}\n[[Category:1829 births]]\n[[Category:1912 deaths]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Burials at St Peter's, Petersham]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Surrey]]\n[[Category:Sheriffs of the City of London]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1880\u20131885]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1885\u20131886]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1886\u20131892]]\n[[Category:19th-century lord mayors of London]]\n[[Category:19th-century British politicians]]\n[[Category:19th-century English politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{More footnotes|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name = Sir John Whittaker Ellis\n|honorific-suffix = [[Baronet|Bt]] [[Justice of the Peace|JP]]\n|image = John Whitaker Ellis Vanity Fair 4 November 1882.jpg\n|caption = Caricature by [[Leslie Ward|Spy]] published in [[Vanity Fair (British magazine 1868-1914)|Vanity Fair]] in 1882.\n|office1 = [[Lord Mayor of the City of London]]\n|term_start1 = 1881\n|term_end1 = 1882\n|predecessor1 = [[William McArthur (Lord Mayor of London)|William McArthur]]\n|successor1 = Henry Knight\n|birth_date = 25 January 1829<ref name=who>\"Ellis, Sir (John) Whittaker, (25 Jan. 1829\u201320 Sept. 1912).\" WHO'S WHO & WHO WAS WHO.  December 01, 2007. Oxford University Press. Date of access 3 Dec. 2019, <https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540891.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-185738></ref>\n|death_date = 20 September 1912 (aged 83)<ref name=who/>\n| nationality = [[British people|British]]\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|alma_mater = Rev. William Allan's School<ref name=who/>\n|spouse = (1) Mary Ann Staples (d. 1901)<br>(2) Marian Bailey<ref name=who/>\n}}\n{{other people|John Ellis}}\n\n[[File:St Peter's Church, Petersham 05.JPG|thumb|Pyramidal [[stone slab]] on massive stone base above his family grave by [[St Peter's Church, Petersham]]]]\n'''Sir John Whittaker Ellis, 1st Baronet''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|JP}}<ref name=who/> (1829-1912) was [[Lord Mayor of London]] for 1881-1882 in which year he was made a baronet.  Two years later he was elected and re-elected [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for eight years, not seeking further re-election.  A very prosperous banking executive, estate agent and auctioneer among his legacies was a fire station at [[Byfleet]], [[Surrey]]; he sat on the boards of various hospitals and his wife was also engaged in charities.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in 1829, Ellis was the fifth son of Joseph Ellis, owner of the [[Star and Garter Hotel, Richmond|Star and Garter Hotel]] in Petersham, [[Richmond, London|Richmond]], Surrey (now London) from 1830\u20131847.\n\nHe set up his family in [[Byfleet]], living for many years at Petersham House/Place (built in High Road {{abbreviation|c.|circa (about)}} 1859, its surviving front block is 15 High Road, used as [[Lloyds Bank]] and a risk consultancy).  After a fire there, Ellis organised Byfleet's first fire brigade. He equipped three of his market/domestic gardeners &ndash; the Place had attached 17 acres<ref>https://maps.nls.uk/geo/explore/#zoom=18&lat=51.3398&lon=-0.4778&layers=168&b=1</ref> &ndash; with three lengths of hose and an obsolete manual pump, put on wheels, kept in a potting shed. \n\nHe was a banking executive, auctioneer and estate agent, as well as holding local government posts including alderman of Broad Street Ward, 1872-1909, [[Sheriff of London]] and Middlesex, 1874-75, [[Lord Mayor of London]], 1881-82, and mayor of Richmond, 1890-91.<ref name=aim>{{cite web | url = http://www.aim25.ac.uk/cgi-bin/vcdf/detail?coll_id=19166&inst_id=118&nv1=search&nv2=| title = ELLIS, Sir John Whittaker (1829-1912)|publisher= AIM25|accessdate = 2012-08-10}}</ref> He was also a magistrate (Justice of the Peace); Governor of the Irish Society, 1882-94, governor of various hospitals and High Sheriff of Surrey, 1899-1900.<ref name=aim/>\n\nHe was elected for one of the two [[Member of Parliament|seats]] for [[Mid Surrey (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Surrey]] at a [[by-election]] in 1884. When that area was abolished he was nominated for and won the [[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885 general election]] and that of the next year for the inceptive [[Kingston-upon-Thames (UK Parliament constituency)|Kingston upon Thames]] seat which took in Richmond but retired in 1892. Hansard records 20 contributions of his, making some each year to 1891 inclusive.<ref>{{hansard-contribs | sir-john-ellis | Sir John Ellis, Bt }}</ref>\n\nOn 6 June 1882 he was made a [[baronet]], of Byfleet in the County of Surrey, and of Hertford Street, Mayfair, in the County of Middlesex,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=25114 |date=2 June 1882 |page=2589 }}</ref> a title which became extinct on his death. He later became the [[Municipal Borough of Richmond (Surrey)|Borough of Richmond]]'s first Mayor, and purchased the site for Richmond\u2019s [[Old Town Hall, Richmond|first town hall]].<ref name=\"Old Town Hall\">{{cite web | url=http://www.richmond.gov.uk/home/leisure_and_culture/local_history_and_heritage/local_studies_collection/local_history_timelines/old_town_hall_timeline.htm | title=Old Town Hall timeline | publisher=[[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]] | work=Local History Timelines | accessdate=18 December 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819091340/http://www.richmond.gov.uk/home/leisure_and_culture/local_history_and_heritage/local_studies_collection/local_history_timelines/old_town_hall_timeline.htm | archive-date=19 August 2016 | url-status=dead }}</ref>  In 1899 he was appointed [[High Sheriff of Surrey]] for the year.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27061|page=1660|date=10 March 1899}}</ref> He remarried in 1903, to Marian Bailey.\n\nHe was appointed Director of Alliance Bank, 1880, then its Chairman, 1883\u201386; and served years as Chairman of Emanuel Hospital to 1909.<ref name=who/>\n\nEllis died without offspring on 20 September 1912 and is buried in [[Petersham Parish Church|St Peter's churchyard, Petersham]].<ref name=\"Local History Notes Petersham\">{{cite web | url=http://www.richmond.gov.uk/local_history_st_peters_petersham.pdf | title=St Peter's Church, Petersham | publisher=[[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]] | work=Local History Notes | accessdate=18 December 2012 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426233438/http://www.richmond.gov.uk/local_history_st_peters_petersham.pdf | archivedate=26 April 2012 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Legacies==\n[[File:Houses_at_Wormleybury_-_geograph.org.uk_-_472899.jpg|thumb|The summary of his probate's extraction states he lived at (the house known as) [[Wormleybury]], Hertfordshire]]\nIn 1885, he funded Byfleet Fire Station which would house a volunteer fire brigade. Initially the [[Civil parishes in England|(civil) Parish]] managed this, renting its building and an engine from Ellis.  The building was used until 1963, latterly as part of the Surrey Fire Brigade. The building is little changed and became a Grade II [[Listed building]] in 2008.<ref>{{NHLE|num=1392421|desc=The Old Fire Station, 40 High Road}}</ref>  15 High Road, his former front block of the family home, is locally listed, under category \"AH\", architectural merit.<ref>[https://www.woking.gov.uk/sites/default/files/documents/planning-and-building-control/herritage/planningheritage.pdf Local Listed Building no. 191], ''The Heritage of Woking'', amended 2000, Borough of Woking: Planning Service, p 12 of 100.</ref>\n\nIn 1895 a bust of Ellis was unveiled in the town hall by [[Princess Mary Adelaide of Cambridge|Mary Adelaide, Duchess of Teck]]<ref name=\"Old Town Hall\"/>  this is still displayed in the staircase alcove.<ref>[http://www.richmond.gov.uk/home/leisure_and_culture/local_history_and_heritage/local_studies_collection/local_history_timelines/old_town_hall_timeline/bust_of_sir_john_wittaker_ellis.htm Photograph and details of bust of Ellis in the Old Town Hall] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120902035640/http://www.richmond.gov.uk/home/leisure_and_culture/local_history_and_heritage/local_studies_collection/local_history_timelines/old_town_hall_timeline/bust_of_sir_john_wittaker_ellis.htm |date=2 September 2012 }} London Borough of Richmond-on-Thames: Local History and Heritage: Old Town Hall Timeline</ref>\n\nHis wife shares a large stone monument above their grave, in the related church he has a plaque in north chancel.<ref name=\"Local History Notes Petersham\"/>\n\nHe is further commemorated by Whittaker Avenue, Richmond.<ref name=\"Local History Notes Petersham\"/>  His probate was resworn in 1912 leaving assets of {{GBP|181969|1912|round=-5|about=yes|long=no}} <ref>https://probatesearch.service.gov.uk Calendar of Probates and Administrations</ref>\n\n==Lady Ellis==\nJohn Whittaker Ellis married, in 1859, Mary Anne Staples, daughter of John Staples.\n\nThe first Lady Ellis was a prominent Mayoress both in London and in Richmond, and was identified with many charities in the then greater forms of [[Surrey]] (reduced to reflect expansion of [[London]] itself in her lifetime and further in 1965). She was president of the Ladies\u00b4 Committee of the Royal Cambridge Asylum for 70 military widows ([[East Molesey]]), and on the death of [[Princess Mary Adelaide of Cambridge|Princess Mary Adelaide, Duchess of Teck]] in 1897 was appointed to succeed her as county president of the Surrey Needlework Guild. She was also one of the presidents of the [[Soldiers' and Sailors' Families Association]] and took a prominent part in the establishment of the [[National Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children|Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children]]. She died at Buccleuch House, [[Richmond, London|Richmond, Surrey]], on 18 December 1901.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Obituaries - Lady Ellis |day_of_week=Thursday |date=19 December 1901 |page_number=6 |issue=36642}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nHe circulated pamphlets entitled or concerning: \"The Land Question, Government of Ireland etc.\"<ref name=who/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Old Town Hall, Richmond]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Byfleet Heritage Society archives\n* Stevens, Leonard R (2001, 2nd edition reprint by the Byfleet Heritage Society) \u2018Byfleet \u2013 A Village of England\u2019 (The Byfleet Heritage Society, Byfleet, Surrey).\n* Wakeford, Iain (1983) \u2018Bygone Woking\u2019 (Phillimore & Co Ltd, Chichester, {{ISBN|0-85033-506-X}}).\n* Wakeford, Iain (2000) \u2018Byfleet \u2013 A Heritage Walks Guide\u2019 (AK, HR & DA Wakeford, Old Woking, Surrey)\n*{{Rayment-bt|date=March 2012}}\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n*[http://www.byfleetheritage.org.uk/ Byfleet Heritage Society website]\n\n== External links ==\n* {{hansard-contribs | sir-john-ellis | Sir John Ellis, Bt }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-civ}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Lord Mayor of the City of London]] | before=[[William McArthur (Lord Mayor of London)|William McArthur]] | after=[[Henry Knight (Lord Mayor of London)|Henry Knight]] | years=1881\u20131882}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Sir Henry Peek, 1st Baronet|Sir Henry Peek, Bt]]\n | before2 = [[Sir Trevor Lawrence, 2nd Baronet|Sir Trevor Lawrence, Bt]]\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Mid Surrey (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Surrey]]\n | years = [[1884 Mid Surrey by-election|1884]] \u2013 [[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885]]\n | with  = [[Sir Trevor Lawrence, 2nd Baronet|Sir Trevor Lawrence, Bt]]\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = Constituency abolished }}\n{{s-new | constituency }}\n{{s-ttl\n  | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Kingston-upon-Thames (UK Parliament constituency)|Kingston]]\n  | years = [[1885 United Kingdom general election|1885]] \u2013 [[1892 United Kingdom general election|1892]]\n}}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[Sir Richard Temple, 1st Baronet|Sir Richard Temple, Bt]] }}\n{{s-reg|uk-bt}}\n{{s-new | creation }}\n{{s-ttl\n  | title  = [[Ellis baronets|Baronet]]<br />'''(of Byfleet and Hertford Street)'''\n  | years  = 1882 \u2013 1912\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = Extinct }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ellis, John}}\n[[Category:1829 births]]\n[[Category:1912 deaths]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Burials at St Peter's, Petersham]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Surrey]]\n[[Category:Sheriffs of the City of London]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1880\u20131885]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1885\u20131886]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1886\u20131892]]\n[[Category:19th-century lord mayors of London]]\n[[Category:19th-century British politicians]]\n[[Category:19th-century English politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1881-1882 \u2192 1881\u20131882, \u2019s \u2192 's, 1872-1909 \u2192 1872\u20131909 (6)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Whittaker_Ellis"}
{"title_page": "Dan McLeod", "text_new": "{{For|the Canadian professional wrestler|Dan McLeod (wrestler)}}\n[[File:Dan Mcleod, Cooktown lo-res.jpg|thumb|240px|Dan McLeod at work near [[Cooktown]], Australia]]\n\n'''Dan McLeod''' (born 1943) is one of the founders and the present owner, publisher, and editor of the influential weekly newspaper, the ''[[Georgia Straight]]'' in [[Vancouver|Vancouver, British Columbia]], Canada.\n\nDan was born and raised in Vancouver. He graduated from [[Kitsilano]] High School and  went on to study mathematics and meteorology at the [[University of British Columbia]],<ref name=\"rickmcgrath.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rickmcgrath.com/georgia_straight/staffers.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 5, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222025442/http://www.rickmcgrath.com/georgia_straight/staffers.html |archivedate=February 22, 2012 }}</ref> where Dan earned an Honours B.Sc degree in mathematics. He was also a poet, and after readings by the poet Charles Duncan (poet) at U.B.C. in the summer of 1961, he, with some friends, began a small newsletter, ''Tish'', which he edited from about 1964 until the ''[[Georgia Straight]]'' was founded in 1967.<ref name=\"chronology1967\">http://www.chuckdavis.ca/chronology1967.htm</ref>\n\n==Foundation of the ''Georgia Straight''==\n:\"Legend has it the joint decision to start a so-called underground newspaper like the [[Village Voice]] was made at a party following a poetry reading by [[Leonard Cohen]]. McLeod emerged as the prime leader behind the idealistic, naive, frequently irresponsible, consistently cheeky, often insightful, collectively-run initiative because he was most willing to take the brunt of police persecution and unmitigated legal harassment that ensued.\"<ref name=\"chronology1967\" />\n\n:In April 1967: \"The proposed paper is christened the ''Georgia Straight'' over beer at the Cecil Hotel. The name aims to play on the fact that the weather forecasts will offer free publicity: they're always issuing gale warnings for the [[Georgia Strait]].\"<ref>''The Georgia Straight: What the Hell Happened''? Naomi Pauls and Charles Campbell, p. 67. (1997) Douglas & McIntyre, Vancouver/Toronto. {{ISBN|1-55054-534-5}}.</ref>\n\nThe paper was founded by [[Pierre Coupey]],<ref name=\"rickmcgrath.com\"/> [[Milton Acorn]],<ref name=\"rickmcgrath.com\"/> Dan McLeod, [[Stan Persky]], and others, and operated originally as a collective.<ref>''The Georgia Straight: What the Hell Happened''? Naomi Pauls and Charles Campbell, p. 20 (1997) Douglas & McIntyre, Vancouver/Toronto. {{ISBN|1-55054-534-5}}.</ref>\n\nThe first issue appeared on 5 May 1967 and cost a dime. It was at first a biweekly. On 12 May the paper moved into its first office at 432 Homer St., and soon after Dan was taken away in a paddy wagon and jailed for three hours for \"investigation of vagrancy.\" College Printers refused to print the second issue,<ref name=\"chronology1967\" /> but an alternative printer was soon found. Dan continued to regularly find himself at odds with the Law, especially in the early days, and was even asked once by a policeman: \"What do you want me to arrest you for\u2014disturbing the peace?\"<ref>''The Georgia Straight: What the Hell Happened''? Naomi Pauls and Charles Campbell, p. 20. (1997) Douglas & McIntyre, Vancouver/Toronto. {{ISBN|1-55054-534-5}}.</ref>\n\n\"The Straight\" soon developed into an anti-establishment [[alternative weekly|alternative newspaper]] with a focus on investigative reporting, and providing a voice for the growing alternative culture in Vancouver, which grew rapidly in the late 1960s with an influx of many thousands of [[Vietnam War]] [[draft dodger]]s and military deserters seeking refuge, as Canada remained technically neutral.<ref name=\"dogers\">[http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2004/09/08/draft_dogers040908.html Draft-dodger memorial to be built in B.C.], CBC News, 09/08/2004</ref> This exodus was \"the largest politically motivated migration from the United States since the [[United Empire Loyalist]]s moved north to oppose the [[American Revolution]].\"<ref name = \"strawberry\">\"On Strawberry Hill\" by Chris Turner in [[The Walrus]], September 2007.</ref>\n\n:\"Then-editor (and now publisher) Dan McLeod was a grad student and a poet who strongly advocated press freedoms. He opened up the pages of the Straight as a forum for alternative opinions, which often got him in trouble with the law. Within the first two years of publication, McLeod and his paper were charged with 27 counts of obscenity, one charge of \"counselling to commit an indictable offence\" (for publishing tips on how to grow marijuana) and one count of criminal libel for comparing a judge to [[Pontius Pilate]].\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rrj.ca/issue/1996/spring/216/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2009-06-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090608081926/http://www.rrj.ca/issue/1996/spring/216 |archive-date=2009-06-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n\nIn 1998 Dan won the  [[Bruce Hutchison]] [[Lifetime Achievement Award]] from the [[Jack Webster (journalist)|Jack Webster]] Foundation.<ref name=\"straight-2000\">https://www.straight.com/article/2-000-issues-and-counting</ref><ref>http://www.jackwebster.com/awards/1998.shtml/images/past_awards.swf{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Dan McLeod was honoured with another Lifetime Achievement Award from the [[Western Magazine Awards|Western Magazine Awards Foundation]].<ref name=\"straight-2000\" /><ref>http://www.sources.com/SSR/Docs/WesternMagazineAwardsWinnners2002.htm</ref><ref>http://www.abcbookworld.com/view_author.php?id=4324</ref>\n\n==Current activities==\n\n{{As of|2009}}, Dan McLeod still owns, edits and publishes the ''Georgia Straight'', and he and his partner Yolanda Stepien, are involved in many [[philanthropic]] and other projects supporting the arts. They have two grown children. Their son, Matt, is currently VP of Operations for the Straight, while Yolanda is the Distribution Director.<ref name=\"rickmcgrath.com\" />\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* ''The Georgia Straight: What the Hell Happened''? Naomi Pauls and Charles Campbell. (1997) Douglas & McIntyre, Vancouver/Toronto. {{ISBN|1-55054-534-5}}.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.straight.com/ ''The Georgia Straight'']\n* For some excellent video clips on the history of the Georgia Straight, go to: [https://www.straight.com/article-161796/last-streetfighter-history-georgia-straight]\n* [https://www.straight.com/article/2-000-issues-and-counting \"2,000 issues and counting.\"] Dave Watson. April 20, 2006.\n* [http://www.abcbookworld.com/view_author.php?id=4324 \"McLeod, Dan\"] on abcbookworld.com\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120222025442/http://www.rickmcgrath.com/georgia_straight/staffers.html \"Storming The Barricades: Vancouver's Underground Press Gangs: 1967-1973.\"]\n* [http://www.vancouverhistory.ca/chronology1967.htm \"The History of Metropolitan Vancouver\"]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090608081926/http://www.rrj.ca/issue/1996/spring/216 \"What a Long Straight Trip It's Been: From rag to respectability: the real dope on Canada's oldest underground weekly.\"] Jennifer Patterson. ''Ryerson Review of Journalism'', Spring 1996.\nThe Last Streetfighter, the history of the Georgia Straight, documentary.\n* https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QykaUVHvags\n <!-- use Mac for Mc in sorts -->\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McLeod, Dan}}\n[[Category:Canadian newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:Canadian newspaper founders]]\n[[Category:Canadian newspaper journalists]]\n[[Category:Canadian male journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian newspaper publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian newspaper publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian poets]]\n[[Category:Canadian male poets]]\n[[Category:Writers from Vancouver]]\n[[Category:University of British Columbia alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the Canadian professional wrestler|Dan McLeod (wrestler)}}\n[[File:Dan Mcleod, Cooktown lo-res.jpg|thumb|240px|Dan McLeod at work near [[Cooktown]], Australia]]\n\n'''Dan McLeod''' (born 1943) is one of the founders and the present owner, publisher, and editor of the influential weekly newspaper, the ''[[Georgia Straight]]'' in [[Vancouver|Vancouver, British Columbia]], Canada.\n\nDan was born and raised in Vancouver. He graduated from [[Kitsilano]] High School and  went on to study mathematics and meteorology at the [[University of British Columbia]],<ref name=\"rickmcgrath.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rickmcgrath.com/georgia_straight/staffers.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 5, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222025442/http://www.rickmcgrath.com/georgia_straight/staffers.html |archivedate=February 22, 2012 }}</ref> where Dan earned an Honours B.Sc degree in mathematics. He was also a poet, and after readings by the poet Charles Duncan (poet) at U.B.C. in the summer of 1961, he, with some friends, began a small newsletter, ''Tish'', which he edited from about 1964 until the ''[[Georgia Straight]]'' was founded in 1967.<ref name=\"chronology1967\">http://www.chuckdavis.ca/chronology1967.htm</ref>\n\n==Foundation of the Georgia Straight==\n:\"Legend has it the joint decision to start a so-called underground newspaper like the [[Village Voice]] was made at a party following a poetry reading by [[Leonard Cohen]]. McLeod emerged as the prime leader behind the idealistic, naive, frequently irresponsible, consistently cheeky, often insightful, collectively-run initiative because he was most willing to take the brunt of police persecution and unmitigated legal harassment that ensued.\"<ref name=\"chronology1967\" />\n\n:In April 1967: \"The proposed paper is christened the ''Georgia Straight'' over beer at the Cecil Hotel. The name aims to play on the fact that the weather forecasts will offer free publicity: they're always issuing gale warnings for the [[Georgia Strait]].\"<ref>''The Georgia Straight: What the Hell Happened''? Naomi Pauls and Charles Campbell, p. 67. (1997) Douglas & McIntyre, Vancouver/Toronto. {{ISBN|1-55054-534-5}}.</ref>\n\nThe paper was founded by [[Pierre Coupey]],<ref name=\"rickmcgrath.com\"/> [[Milton Acorn]],<ref name=\"rickmcgrath.com\"/> Dan McLeod, [[Stan Persky]], and others, and operated originally as a collective.<ref>''The Georgia Straight: What the Hell Happened''? Naomi Pauls and Charles Campbell, p. 20 (1997) Douglas & McIntyre, Vancouver/Toronto. {{ISBN|1-55054-534-5}}.</ref>\n\nThe first issue appeared on 5 May 1967 and cost a dime. It was at first a biweekly. On 12 May the paper moved into its first office at 432 Homer St., and soon after Dan was taken away in a paddy wagon and jailed for three hours for \"investigation of vagrancy.\" College Printers refused to print the second issue,<ref name=\"chronology1967\" /> but an alternative printer was soon found. Dan continued to regularly find himself at odds with the Law, especially in the early days, and was even asked once by a policeman: \"What do you want me to arrest you for\u2014disturbing the peace?\"<ref>''The Georgia Straight: What the Hell Happened''? Naomi Pauls and Charles Campbell, p. 20. (1997) Douglas & McIntyre, Vancouver/Toronto. {{ISBN|1-55054-534-5}}.</ref>\n\n\"The Straight\" soon developed into an anti-establishment [[alternative weekly|alternative newspaper]] with a focus on investigative reporting, and providing a voice for the growing alternative culture in Vancouver, which grew rapidly in the late 1960s with an influx of many thousands of [[Vietnam War]] [[draft dodger]]s and military deserters seeking refuge, as Canada remained technically neutral.<ref name=\"dogers\">[http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2004/09/08/draft_dogers040908.html Draft-dodger memorial to be built in B.C.], CBC News, 09/08/2004</ref> This exodus was \"the largest politically motivated migration from the United States since the [[United Empire Loyalist]]s moved north to oppose the [[American Revolution]].\"<ref name = \"strawberry\">\"On Strawberry Hill\" by Chris Turner in [[The Walrus]], September 2007.</ref>\n\n:\"Then-editor (and now publisher) Dan McLeod was a grad student and a poet who strongly advocated press freedoms. He opened up the pages of the Straight as a forum for alternative opinions, which often got him in trouble with the law. Within the first two years of publication, McLeod and his paper were charged with 27 counts of obscenity, one charge of \"counselling to commit an indictable offence\" (for publishing tips on how to grow marijuana) and one count of criminal libel for comparing a judge to [[Pontius Pilate]].\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rrj.ca/issue/1996/spring/216/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2009-06-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090608081926/http://www.rrj.ca/issue/1996/spring/216 |archive-date=2009-06-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n\nIn 1998 Dan won the  [[Bruce Hutchison]] [[Lifetime Achievement Award]] from the [[Jack Webster (journalist)|Jack Webster]] Foundation.<ref name=\"straight-2000\">https://www.straight.com/article/2-000-issues-and-counting</ref><ref>http://www.jackwebster.com/awards/1998.shtml/images/past_awards.swf{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Dan McLeod was honoured with another Lifetime Achievement Award from the [[Western Magazine Awards|Western Magazine Awards Foundation]].<ref name=\"straight-2000\" /><ref>http://www.sources.com/SSR/Docs/WesternMagazineAwardsWinnners2002.htm</ref><ref>http://www.abcbookworld.com/view_author.php?id=4324</ref>\n\n==Current activities==\n\n{{As of|2009}}, Dan McLeod still owns, edits and publishes the ''Georgia Straight'', and he and his partner Yolanda Stepien, are involved in many [[philanthropic]] and other projects supporting the arts. They have two grown children. Their son, Matt, is currently VP of Operations for the Straight, while Yolanda is the Distribution Director.<ref name=\"rickmcgrath.com\" />\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* ''The Georgia Straight: What the Hell Happened''? Naomi Pauls and Charles Campbell. (1997) Douglas & McIntyre, Vancouver/Toronto. {{ISBN|1-55054-534-5}}.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.straight.com/ ''The Georgia Straight'']\n* For some excellent video clips on the history of the Georgia Straight, go to: [https://www.straight.com/article-161796/last-streetfighter-history-georgia-straight]\n* [https://www.straight.com/article/2-000-issues-and-counting \"2,000 issues and counting.\"] Dave Watson. April 20, 2006.\n* [http://www.abcbookworld.com/view_author.php?id=4324 \"McLeod, Dan\"] on abcbookworld.com\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120222025442/http://www.rickmcgrath.com/georgia_straight/staffers.html \"Storming The Barricades: Vancouver's Underground Press Gangs: 1967-1973.\"]\n* [http://www.vancouverhistory.ca/chronology1967.htm \"The History of Metropolitan Vancouver\"]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090608081926/http://www.rrj.ca/issue/1996/spring/216 \"What a Long Straight Trip It's Been: From rag to respectability: the real dope on Canada's oldest underground weekly.\"] Jennifer Patterson. ''Ryerson Review of Journalism'', Spring 1996.\nThe Last Streetfighter, the history of the Georgia Straight, documentary.\n* https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QykaUVHvags\n <!-- use Mac for Mc in sorts -->\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McLeod, Dan}}\n[[Category:Canadian newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:Canadian newspaper founders]]\n[[Category:Canadian newspaper journalists]]\n[[Category:Canadian male journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian newspaper publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian newspaper publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian poets]]\n[[Category:Canadian male poets]]\n[[Category:Writers from Vancouver]]\n[[Category:University of British Columbia alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "Section heading change: Foundation of the Georgia Straight \u2192 Foundation of the ''Georgia Straight'' using ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dan_McLeod"}
